262
00:16:17,072 --> 00:16:19,341
Is this the Dollar Ride?

263
00:16:21,360 --> 00:16:22,527
Good.

264
00:16:22,595 --> 00:16:24,763
Does your transportation
services

265
00:16:24,830 --> 00:16:26,898
accommodate
the handicapped?

266
00:16:28,534 --> 00:16:30,168
Excellent, sir,

267
00:16:30,235 --> 00:16:33,972
because if you did not
accommodate the handicapped,

268
00:16:34,040 --> 00:16:37,408
I would sue
your unaccommodating ass.

269
00:16:53,292 --> 00:16:55,677
[music playing]

270
00:16:55,745 --> 00:16:57,478
Buenas días, señoritas.

271
00:16:57,546 --> 00:16:59,163
I don't know about you,

272
00:16:59,231 --> 00:17:02,200
but this music makes me
feel like dancing.

273
00:17:14,630 --> 00:17:16,580
Two Ding Dongs...

274
00:17:16,649 --> 00:17:18,016
[cash register
beeping]

275
00:17:18,150 --> 00:17:20,217
bag of Cheetos...

276
00:17:20,285 --> 00:17:21,820
[beeping]

277
00:17:23,388 --> 00:17:28,860
and a box
of gluten-free
Fruity Pebbles.

278
00:17:32,030 --> 00:17:33,665
Will that be all?

279
00:17:33,732 --> 00:17:38,102
Uh, I'll have another
bottle of your finest
sour mash whiskey.

280
00:17:41,257 --> 00:17:43,023
[beeping]

281
00:17:45,261 --> 00:17:46,494
[beeping]

282
00:17:46,562 --> 00:17:49,830
That will be $37.42.

283
00:17:49,898 --> 00:17:51,416
Take it out of that.

284
00:17:52,751 --> 00:17:54,502
So, it's Mahmoud,
is it?

285
00:17:54,570 --> 00:17:56,037
Yes, sir.

286
00:17:56,104 --> 00:17:58,239
Here is your change.

287
00:17:58,307 --> 00:17:59,908
Uh-oh.

288
00:17:59,975 --> 00:18:01,826
What?

289
00:18:01,894 --> 00:18:05,329
Classic check-out stand
blunder.

290
00:18:05,397 --> 00:18:06,648
What is?

291
00:18:06,715 --> 00:18:09,033
In a word,
Slim Jims.

292
00:18:09,101 --> 00:18:13,054
Isn't that...
two words?

293
00:18:13,122 --> 00:18:16,273
You're taking your eye
off the ball, Mahmoud.

294
00:18:16,341 --> 00:18:18,293
What ball?

295
00:18:18,361 --> 00:18:22,880
I realize that it is
considered by many

296
00:18:22,948 --> 00:18:26,050
to be an on-the-way-out
kind of item,

297
00:18:26,117 --> 00:18:29,721
but I believe that
to be a rural myth.

298
00:18:29,788 --> 00:18:31,956
Don't get me wrong.

299
00:18:32,023 --> 00:18:33,691
If you have a hankering
for Slim Jims,

300
00:18:33,759 --> 00:18:34,926
you'll hunt the store over,

301
00:18:34,993 --> 00:18:36,711
but if not,

302
00:18:36,779 --> 00:18:38,579
a desperate display
like this

303
00:18:38,647 --> 00:18:40,815
improves no one's life.

304
00:18:41,684 --> 00:18:43,334
What do you suggest?

305
00:18:43,402 --> 00:18:44,635
Sunflower seeds.

306
00:18:45,604 --> 00:18:46,754
Just a thought.

307
00:18:46,989 --> 00:18:49,690
Good day.
Good day.

308
00:18:53,162 --> 00:18:54,862
CHARLOTTE:
Come on.

309
00:18:54,930 --> 00:18:56,897
You're
such a good boy.

310
00:18:58,633 --> 00:18:59,567
Hi.

311
00:19:00,902 --> 00:19:02,570
We haven't formally met.

312
00:19:02,637 --> 00:19:04,105
I'm Charlotte O'Neil.

313
00:19:04,173 --> 00:19:07,959
Pleasure, Mrs. O'Neil.
Monte Wildhorn.

314
00:19:08,027 --> 00:19:11,796
I should explain. I have
a rather long-standing
arrangement with Dave,

315
00:19:12,098 --> 00:19:14,149
since he's away
a lot with his band.

316
00:19:14,216 --> 00:19:17,485
And, while he's gone,
I take care of Ringo.

317
00:19:17,552 --> 00:19:20,905
You're not, by any chance,
referring to Spot, are you?

318
00:19:20,972 --> 00:19:24,291
Oh, a new name?

319
00:19:24,359 --> 00:19:26,093
Well, I've known him
since he was a pup.

320
00:19:26,161 --> 00:19:27,545
Well, there's a lot
to be said

321
00:19:27,612 --> 00:19:30,014
for enduring
associations,
Mrs. O'Neil,

322
00:19:30,082 --> 00:19:31,515
but in the future,

323
00:19:31,583 --> 00:19:34,585
I'd appreciate it
if you wouldn't walk
my dog.

324
00:19:34,653 --> 00:19:35,920
He's Dave's dog.

325
00:19:35,988 --> 00:19:38,856
I'm not claiming to be
his biological father.

326
00:19:38,924 --> 00:19:41,993
Oh... um...

327
00:19:42,061 --> 00:19:44,211
This is Flora,
my youngest.

328
00:19:45,848 --> 00:19:48,983
Well, as long as you think
you can manage, Mr. Wildhorn.

329
00:19:49,050 --> 00:19:52,487
And why wouldn't I be able
to manage, Mrs. O'Neil?

330
00:19:52,555 --> 00:19:54,222
No reason.

331
00:19:55,657 --> 00:19:57,175
Come here.

332
00:19:57,927 --> 00:20:00,845
Oh, um, just so you know.

333
00:20:00,913 --> 00:20:02,847
Uh, Ringo--

334
00:20:02,915 --> 00:20:06,250
Um, sorry, Spot.

335
00:20:06,318 --> 00:20:08,653
He tends to get stiff
in his hindquarters.

336
00:20:08,720 --> 00:20:10,671
He needs daily exercise.

337
00:20:10,740 --> 00:20:12,440
I'll take it
under advisement.

338
00:20:15,527 --> 00:20:19,414
Now, I'm willing
to meet you halfway.

339
00:20:19,482 --> 00:20:22,350
You miss Dave.
I understand that.

340
00:20:22,417 --> 00:20:24,352
But your friend
Mrs. O'Neil

341
00:20:24,419 --> 00:20:26,755
had no right
to take you for a walk

342
00:20:26,822 --> 00:20:28,823
without asking me first.

343
00:20:28,891 --> 00:20:30,258
In the future,

344
00:20:30,325 --> 00:20:33,695
you will politely decline
all such invitations.

345
00:20:33,763 --> 00:20:34,696
Is that clear?

346
00:20:38,117 --> 00:20:39,968
Now that cannot
be the response

347
00:20:40,035 --> 00:20:41,669
to every admonishment.

348
00:20:41,737 --> 00:20:42,587
[Spot/Ringo snorts]

349
00:20:42,655 --> 00:20:44,305
[knock on door]

350
00:20:44,373 --> 00:20:45,840
Al Kaiser!

351
00:20:45,908 --> 00:20:46,974
I'm just down the road.

352
00:20:47,042 --> 00:20:49,293
Got the old outboard
in the driveway.

353
00:20:49,361 --> 00:20:51,763
Oh, where are
my manners?

354
00:20:51,830 --> 00:20:53,748
Do come in,
Mr. Kaiser.

355
00:20:53,816 --> 00:20:56,116
Can I offer you
a Ding Dong?

356
00:20:56,184 --> 00:20:57,601
Uh, sorry. I can't stay.

357
00:20:57,669 --> 00:21:00,071
I'm having a memorial
for Don at my house.

358
00:21:00,139 --> 00:21:02,389
Ah, the basketball
aficionado.

359
00:21:02,457 --> 00:21:04,275
Yes.
It was quite a shock.

360
00:21:04,343 --> 00:21:06,043
Yeah, well, not to me.

361
00:21:06,111 --> 00:21:08,279
Well, I hope
you can make it.

362
00:21:08,346 --> 00:21:10,197
Uh, I didn't know
the man.

363
00:21:10,266 --> 00:21:11,766
Everybody's bringing
something.

364
00:21:11,833 --> 00:21:14,018
You know, potluck.
See you around 5:00.

365
00:21:14,086 --> 00:21:15,904
I didn't know
the man.

366
00:21:15,971 --> 00:21:17,388
See you then!

367
00:21:19,892 --> 00:21:22,526
WILLOW: Did I
miss Daddy's call?

368
00:21:22,594 --> 00:21:23,661
Daddy will call you

369
00:21:23,729 --> 00:21:25,529
as soon as he has
time, Willow Tree.

370
00:21:25,597 --> 00:21:27,999
Daddy promised to
help me finish my raft.

371
00:21:28,067 --> 00:21:30,267
I'm going to the island
this summer.

372
00:21:30,335 --> 00:21:32,370
What's so important
about that stupid
island, anyway?

373
00:21:33,388 --> 00:21:34,838
That's where
the magic is.

374
00:21:35,107 --> 00:21:36,507
You're delusional.

375
00:21:36,575 --> 00:21:37,925
Willow.

376
00:21:37,993 --> 00:21:39,444
I just don't understand

377
00:21:39,511 --> 00:21:41,162
why I couldn't have
stayed with Dad.

378
00:21:41,229 --> 00:21:43,248
I'd like the two of you
to take the salad

379
00:21:43,315 --> 00:21:44,849
down the block
to Don's memorial.

380
00:21:44,916 --> 00:21:46,517
I'm busy.

381
00:21:46,585 --> 00:21:48,386
I'll go, Mama.

382
00:21:48,453 --> 00:21:50,037
Thank you, Finn.

383
00:21:50,105 --> 00:21:51,589
What do I do?

384
00:21:51,656 --> 00:21:54,742
You offer our family's
condolences,

385
00:21:54,810 --> 00:21:57,011
and then you leave the salad
and come straight home.

386
00:21:57,079 --> 00:21:58,412
What's condolences?

387
00:21:58,647 --> 00:22:02,150
You say, "We're very sorry
that Don has passed,

388
00:22:02,218 --> 00:22:03,985
but now he's
with all of us."

389
00:22:04,053 --> 00:22:05,620
He is?

390
00:22:05,821 --> 00:22:08,238
Just drop off the salad
and look sad.

391
00:22:08,306 --> 00:22:11,426
Ah, I'm so glad
you made it.

392
00:22:12,194 --> 00:22:13,311
I brought you Cheetos.

393
00:22:13,478 --> 00:22:15,429
Nice touch. Welcome.

394
00:22:17,098 --> 00:22:18,232
Uh, thanks.

395
00:22:18,300 --> 00:22:19,767
There's plenty to eat,

396
00:22:19,834 --> 00:22:21,068
and the beer is on ice,

397
00:22:21,136 --> 00:22:24,004
just the way Don
would have wanted.

398
00:22:24,072 --> 00:22:26,174
A lot of nice
people here.

399
00:22:26,241 --> 00:22:27,741
I think you'll
like everybody.

400
00:22:29,911 --> 00:22:31,111
I must say,

401
00:22:31,180 --> 00:22:33,881
I'm a big admirer
of your work.

402
00:22:33,948 --> 00:22:35,449
Thank you.

403
00:22:35,517 --> 00:22:37,317
I haven't been a dog-sitter
for very long.

404
00:22:37,385 --> 00:22:38,452
No, I'm talking about

405
00:22:38,520 --> 00:22:40,755
those Western novels
you write.

406
00:22:40,823 --> 00:22:42,824
I've got a copy of
Showdown at Red Rock

407
00:22:42,891 --> 00:22:44,792
around somewhere.

408
00:22:44,859 --> 00:22:46,210
It's been out of print
for years.

409
00:22:46,278 --> 00:22:48,279
Uh, you mentioned beer?

410
00:22:48,346 --> 00:22:49,664
Beer.
Indeed I did.

411
00:22:51,683 --> 00:22:52,967
Hi, Finn.

412
00:22:53,035 --> 00:22:55,136
Sorry Don died.
Here's a salad.

413
00:22:55,203 --> 00:22:57,271
Don would've
appreciated that.

414
00:22:57,339 --> 00:22:59,073
And thank
your mother for me.

415
00:22:59,141 --> 00:23:00,775
You can add the salad
to that table,

416
00:23:00,843 --> 00:23:03,811
and be an angel
and drop that off, too.

417
00:23:03,879 --> 00:23:06,714
One of the O'Neil
girls.

418
00:23:06,782 --> 00:23:08,032
Sweet kids.

419
00:23:08,099 --> 00:23:09,767
Monte Wildhorn,
may I present

420
00:23:09,835 --> 00:23:12,804
Miss Finnegan O'Neil
of Belle Isle.

421
00:23:13,839 --> 00:23:15,373
Pleased to make
your acquaintance.

422
00:23:15,540 --> 00:23:17,307
Can I get more beer?

423
00:23:17,375 --> 00:23:18,642
Ah.

424
00:23:18,710 --> 00:23:20,811
Mr. Wildhorn
writes about cowboys

425
00:23:20,879 --> 00:23:22,080
in the Wild West.

426
00:23:22,147 --> 00:23:24,349
Boy, I'll say one thing.

427
00:23:24,416 --> 00:23:27,568
That Jubal McLaws
sure is quick on the draw.

428
00:23:27,636 --> 00:23:30,988
Many cross his path.
Few live to tell about it.

429
00:23:31,056 --> 00:23:32,272
Now, that's right,

430
00:23:32,340 --> 00:23:33,674
like when Jubal
had that shootout

431
00:23:33,742 --> 00:23:36,543
with Deadshot Jim Watson
of Albuquerque.

432
00:23:36,612 --> 00:23:37,979
Whoo!

433
00:23:38,046 --> 00:23:39,714
Say, if I could find my copy

434
00:23:39,781 --> 00:23:42,216
of Showdown at Red Rock,
would you sign it for me?

435
00:23:42,283 --> 00:23:43,868
I would not, Mr. Kaiser.

436
00:23:43,936 --> 00:23:48,139
I've always resisted becoming
part of the cult of celebrity.

437
00:23:48,207 --> 00:23:50,374
However...

438
00:23:50,442 --> 00:23:51,675
I will accept
another beer.

439
00:23:51,827 --> 00:23:54,862
Ah! All right.
I respect that.

440
00:24:04,640 --> 00:24:06,573
I'm not really
from Belle Isle.

441
00:24:06,642 --> 00:24:09,309
We only come here
for the summers.

442
00:24:10,245 --> 00:24:11,595
Is that so?

443
00:24:12,264 --> 00:24:13,615
I live in Manhattan.

444
00:24:15,283 --> 00:24:17,418
At least, I used to.

445
00:24:17,486 --> 00:24:18,953
My dad and mom are
getting divorced,

446
00:24:19,021 --> 00:24:20,187
so now my mom says

447
00:24:20,255 --> 00:24:21,789
we have to live
here all the time.

448
00:24:21,857 --> 00:24:22,606
Hmm...

449
00:24:24,526 --> 00:24:26,828
How come your mom let you
come to an event like this

450
00:24:26,895 --> 00:24:28,312
all by your lonesome?

451
00:24:28,380 --> 00:24:30,447
'Cause I'm 9 1/2 years old.

452
00:24:30,515 --> 00:24:33,367
Hmm, that's pretty old.
I know.

453
00:24:33,435 --> 00:24:35,653
My mom even lets me have
my own pocket knife.

454
00:24:35,787 --> 00:24:38,122
You don't have
no pocket knife.

455
00:24:38,190 --> 00:24:40,825
I do so.
Do not.

456
00:24:45,697 --> 00:24:47,231
My, my.

457
00:24:48,200 --> 00:24:50,834
Look at that.

458
00:24:50,902 --> 00:24:53,003
That must be about
the finest pocket knife

459
00:24:53,072 --> 00:24:55,005
I have ever seen.

460
00:24:56,608 --> 00:24:57,875
You know,
you can tell a lot

461
00:24:57,943 --> 00:24:58,959
about a person's
character

462
00:24:58,944 --> 00:25:01,162
by the condition
of their pocket knife.

463
00:25:01,230 --> 00:25:04,315
I'd say
you were fearless.

464
00:25:14,159 --> 00:25:15,492
What's his problem?

465
00:25:15,560 --> 00:25:18,396
Oh, he's just
being Carl Loop.

466
00:25:18,463 --> 00:25:21,215
Willow says he's retarded,
but Mom says he's special.

467
00:25:21,550 --> 00:25:23,384
Hmm. Well,
whatever he is,

468
00:25:23,452 --> 00:25:25,286
he's a fine dancer.

469
00:25:27,189 --> 00:25:28,488
You write stories?

470
00:25:30,892 --> 00:25:32,326
I used to.

471
00:25:32,393 --> 00:25:35,412
My favorite story is about
aliens from outer space.

472
00:25:35,480 --> 00:25:38,900
Mm. Extraterrestrials
have their place,

473
00:25:38,967 --> 00:25:41,201
and I've met a few,

474
00:25:41,269 --> 00:25:43,004
but you don't have
to leave this planet

475
00:25:43,071 --> 00:25:44,705
to tell a good story.

476
00:25:46,875 --> 00:25:48,142
How...

477
00:25:48,210 --> 00:25:49,276
How do you make 'em up?

478
00:25:49,344 --> 00:25:51,128
Imagination.

479
00:25:51,196 --> 00:25:52,563
The most powerful force

480
00:25:52,631 --> 00:25:55,032
ever made available
to humankind.

481
00:25:57,152 --> 00:25:57,985
Here you go.

482
00:26:00,772 --> 00:26:03,040
Hey, Monte,
I'm no professional,

483
00:26:03,108 --> 00:26:05,376
but I wrote this speech
for Don,

484
00:26:05,444 --> 00:26:08,446
but I'll never be able
to get through it.

485
00:26:08,514 --> 00:26:10,181
I was gonna ask you
to read it out loud.

486
00:26:10,249 --> 00:26:11,849
I've always
had a disdain

487
00:26:11,916 --> 00:26:14,902
for public displays
of sentimentality,
Mr. Kaiser.

488
00:26:14,969 --> 00:26:18,005
Hey, who doesn't?
Don would be so pleased.

489
00:26:18,073 --> 00:26:18,872
Didn't know the man.

490
00:26:18,941 --> 00:26:21,341
Monte has something
he wants to read to us

491
00:26:21,410 --> 00:26:22,710
about Don.

492
00:26:22,911 --> 00:26:24,345
So, if you would,
just step outside

493
00:26:24,413 --> 00:26:25,879
as quickly as you can.

494
00:26:25,947 --> 00:26:28,799
Thank you so much.
He's very excited about this.

495
00:26:28,867 --> 00:26:30,868
Hi, nice to see you. I didn't
get a chance to say hello.

496
00:26:30,935 --> 00:26:33,237
Oh, I didn't know you were
here. Hi. Welcome.

497
00:26:33,372 --> 00:26:36,057
All right, people, this is
a sad and happy occasion.

498
00:26:36,125 --> 00:26:37,458
Thanks for coming here.

499
00:26:37,760 --> 00:26:41,111
Everybody please say hello
to Monte Wildhorn.

500
00:26:56,294 --> 00:26:58,479
"'Jesus H. Christ.'"

501
00:27:00,565 --> 00:27:02,933
"According to our friend
Karen Loop,

502
00:27:03,001 --> 00:27:05,019
"that's how most people
around the lake reacted

503
00:27:05,087 --> 00:27:08,239
"when they heard the news
of Don's passing.

504
00:27:08,306 --> 00:27:11,042
"That's not such a bad obit.

505
00:27:11,109 --> 00:27:14,478
"Concise.
Even rather eloquent.

506
00:27:14,779 --> 00:27:16,898
"Don would've approved.

507
00:27:16,965 --> 00:27:19,901
"There are people in life
you avoid,

508
00:27:19,968 --> 00:27:22,870
"and others you go
out of your way to bump into.

509
00:27:22,938 --> 00:27:26,173
"Don had that bump-into
quality about him,

510
00:27:26,341 --> 00:27:30,711
"which is why nobody ever ducked
when they saw Don coming.

511
00:27:30,779 --> 00:27:34,414
"He took beer very seriously.

512
00:27:34,482 --> 00:27:37,284
"It had to be Pabst Blue Ribbon.

513
00:27:37,352 --> 00:27:39,820
"If it couldn't be Pabst,

514
00:27:39,888 --> 00:27:41,588
"it at least had to be cold.

515
00:27:41,656 --> 00:27:44,158
"As good as Don was,

516
00:27:44,226 --> 00:27:48,829
"I think he only got better
once he found the Belle.

517
00:27:48,897 --> 00:27:52,082
"There just might be something
special about this place.

518
00:27:52,150 --> 00:27:55,686
"It don't happen too often,
but sometimes

519
00:27:55,753 --> 00:27:59,590
"we do bring out
the best in each other.

520
00:27:59,657 --> 00:28:02,226
"We'll miss you, Don.

521
00:28:02,294 --> 00:28:04,962
Watch over us."

522
00:28:09,100 --> 00:28:11,902
Don't change a word.

523
00:28:11,970 --> 00:28:13,437
The man at Dog Dave's
writes stories

524
00:28:13,505 --> 00:28:15,722
about cowboys
in the Wild West.

525
00:28:15,790 --> 00:28:17,358
He does?

526
00:28:17,425 --> 00:28:19,526
Yeah...
not about space aliens.

527
00:28:19,594 --> 00:28:21,095
No aliens?

528
00:28:21,162 --> 00:28:22,796
Mm-mm.

529
00:28:22,864 --> 00:28:24,598
You know, you don't have
to go off this planet

530
00:28:24,665 --> 00:28:26,867
to tell a good story.

531
00:28:26,935 --> 00:28:30,170
Mama, when we get home,
can I work on my raft?

532
00:28:30,238 --> 00:28:33,507
No, you promised
you'd clean your room.

533
00:28:33,574 --> 00:28:36,043
Well,
Jesus H. Christ!

534
00:28:36,894 --> 00:28:38,078
Ms. O'Neil.

535
00:28:38,146 --> 00:28:41,782
That is a most unbecoming
use of language.

536
00:28:41,849 --> 00:28:44,185
Mr. Kaiser wrote it
about Don.

537
00:28:44,252 --> 00:28:46,286
You're not Mr. Kaiser.

538
00:28:46,354 --> 00:28:48,288
Am I in trouble?

539
00:28:48,356 --> 00:28:50,024
You most certainly are,

540
00:28:50,091 --> 00:28:51,191
and your punishment

541
00:28:51,259 --> 00:28:52,759
is to memorize
three new words

542
00:28:52,827 --> 00:28:55,595
and define them for me
by dinner Friday.

543
00:28:55,663 --> 00:28:57,614
And I expect
to be impressed.

544
00:28:57,682 --> 00:28:59,683
You will be.
I promise.

545
00:29:01,203 --> 00:29:02,236
Hmm.

546
00:29:10,445 --> 00:29:12,596
Who does your taxes?

547
00:29:12,664 --> 00:29:14,931
I am currently
without an accountant,

548
00:29:14,999 --> 00:29:16,133
Mrs. Loop.

549
00:29:16,201 --> 00:29:17,768
Karen.

550
00:29:17,835 --> 00:29:19,503
I have aspired
for years

551
00:29:19,571 --> 00:29:21,938
to someday attain
the poverty level.

552
00:29:22,006 --> 00:29:24,608
Having recently
achieved my goal,

553
00:29:24,676 --> 00:29:27,811
I'm not in need of
such services just now.

554
00:29:27,879 --> 00:29:31,081
I always get my clients
a big refund.

555
00:29:31,149 --> 00:29:35,419
You have a positive
outlook on life, Karen.

556
00:29:35,487 --> 00:29:37,321
This is our place.

557
00:29:37,389 --> 00:29:40,090
Thanks for
walking us home.

558
00:29:40,158 --> 00:29:42,693
You and the boy
on your own out here?

559
00:29:42,760 --> 00:29:45,379
My old man took off
after Carl was born.

560
00:29:45,447 --> 00:29:47,197
I'm sorry to hear that.

561
00:29:48,400 --> 00:29:50,567
It's no great loss.

562
00:29:50,635 --> 00:29:53,737
Well, if there's
anything I can do.

563
00:29:53,905 --> 00:29:56,957
Carl never gets
any phone calls.

564
00:29:57,158 --> 00:30:00,644
It would be nice for him
to get a phone call.

565
00:30:00,712 --> 00:30:02,846
Here's my business card.

566
00:30:04,632 --> 00:30:07,151
It's got our
home number on it.

567
00:30:08,553 --> 00:30:10,353
Telephone's
a damn nuisance.

568
00:30:10,622 --> 00:30:13,307
Ain't got
no use for it.

569
00:30:13,375 --> 00:30:14,775
And them people
on cell phones

570
00:30:14,843 --> 00:30:16,844
oughta be shot dead
in the street.

571
00:30:25,369 --> 00:30:26,920
Hey, Carl.

572
00:30:33,878 --> 00:30:36,580
How'd you like to be
my faithful sidekick,

573
00:30:36,648 --> 00:30:37,948
Diego Santana?

574
00:30:38,015 --> 00:30:41,185
Wanted for train robbery
in three territories.

575
00:30:41,253 --> 00:30:42,853
I am?

576
00:30:42,921 --> 00:30:46,973
Railroad Pinkertons are
hot on our trail, amigo.

577
00:30:48,843 --> 00:30:50,110
How do I be Diego?

578
00:30:50,212 --> 00:30:53,813
Well, for starters,
lose the bunny hop.

579
00:30:59,270 --> 00:31:01,204
[chuckling]

580
00:31:08,846 --> 00:31:11,147
[snoring]

581
00:31:20,358 --> 00:31:23,960
Yeah, I'm touched
by your concern.

582
00:31:24,028 --> 00:31:25,962
Thank God
I'm still drinking.

583
00:31:26,030 --> 00:31:28,532
Saves me the humiliation
of falling off the wagon.

584
00:31:28,600 --> 00:31:30,700
FINN:
I need three words.

585
00:31:30,768 --> 00:31:33,336
Have we met?

586
00:31:38,442 --> 00:31:40,377
Did I extend an invitation?

587
00:31:40,444 --> 00:31:41,812
No.

588
00:31:41,880 --> 00:31:44,047
I didn't think so.

589
00:31:45,383 --> 00:31:48,418
You know a lot of good words
'cause you write stories.

590
00:31:48,486 --> 00:31:50,387
I need three good ones
for my mom.

591
00:31:50,454 --> 00:31:53,256
I lost all my good
words a long time ago.

592
00:31:53,324 --> 00:31:55,275
What about imagination?

593
00:31:55,343 --> 00:31:57,244
Should I use that one?

594
00:31:57,312 --> 00:32:00,147
Last time I checked,
it was still available.

595
00:32:00,315 --> 00:32:03,084
Can you teach me
to write stories?

596
00:32:03,151 --> 00:32:06,770
You are
awfully demanding.

597
00:32:08,506 --> 00:32:10,440
All right, Spot.

598
00:32:10,508 --> 00:32:12,977
Time for
our morning dose.

599
00:32:15,079 --> 00:32:17,298
[stirring mixture]

600
00:32:19,801 --> 00:32:21,134
There you go.

601
00:32:22,270 --> 00:32:24,004
That's a good boy.

602
00:32:24,072 --> 00:32:26,173
How come you
give him aspirin?

603
00:32:26,241 --> 00:32:27,841
Uh, it seems Spot
has developed

604
00:32:27,908 --> 00:32:29,843
some stiffness
in his hindquarters.

605
00:32:30,995 --> 00:32:32,646
And aspirin helps that.

606
00:32:34,732 --> 00:32:35,865
I'm not exactly sure,

607
00:32:35,933 --> 00:32:38,202
but long as
he thinks it does,

608
00:32:38,269 --> 00:32:39,969
that's half
the battle, isn't it?

609
00:32:44,292 --> 00:32:46,860
How come you don't
write on a computer?

610
00:32:49,664 --> 00:32:51,432
I'm gonna
answer your question

611
00:32:51,500 --> 00:32:53,767
in return
for blessed silence.

612
00:32:59,508 --> 00:33:01,175
Look at that machine.

613
00:33:01,926 --> 00:33:03,644
I like that you
have to write

614
00:33:03,711 --> 00:33:05,945
a bit slower
on a manual.

615
00:33:06,013 --> 00:33:08,114
I like the way
it sounds.

616
00:33:08,216 --> 00:33:11,802
I like
the way the letters

617
00:33:11,870 --> 00:33:13,470
bite into the paper.

618
00:33:15,173 --> 00:33:17,675
I like that you can feel
there's a genuine human being

619
00:33:17,742 --> 00:33:19,509
doing the work--
Hands off.

620
00:33:24,049 --> 00:33:25,265
What's that?

621
00:33:26,985 --> 00:33:29,252
Buckaroo.
What's a Buckaroo?

622
00:33:29,320 --> 00:33:32,272
It's an award
for literary excellence.

623
00:33:32,340 --> 00:33:36,393
"Western Authors Academy.
Best Western novel.

624
00:33:36,461 --> 00:33:37,961
'The Saga of Jubal McLaws.'

625
00:33:38,028 --> 00:33:41,031
Presented
to Monte Wildhorn. 1975."

626
00:33:41,099 --> 00:33:44,034
Cool. Did you give
a speech when you won?

627
00:33:44,101 --> 00:33:46,453
Yes, ma'am, I did.

628
00:33:46,521 --> 00:33:48,255
Who'd you thank?

629
00:33:48,322 --> 00:33:51,024
My one true love
and three bartenders.

630
00:33:53,694 --> 00:33:55,595
How come you can't walk?

631
00:33:57,582 --> 00:33:59,516
Who says I can't?

632
00:34:02,571 --> 00:34:04,405
Why are you
in a wheelchair?

633
00:34:05,873 --> 00:34:07,391
Can you keep a secret?

634
00:34:10,828 --> 00:34:12,212
Even if they torture me.

635
00:34:14,599 --> 00:34:16,250
I'm attempting to defraud

636
00:34:16,318 --> 00:34:18,619
the Liberty Mutual
insurance conglomerate

637
00:34:18,687 --> 00:34:20,387
out of a million dollars.

638
00:34:21,706 --> 00:34:22,873
What's defraud?

639
00:34:22,941 --> 00:34:26,710
Cheat, snooker,
fleece, bamboozle.

640
00:34:26,778 --> 00:34:29,579
So you can walk?

641
00:34:29,647 --> 00:34:31,431
I can run.

642
00:34:32,950 --> 00:34:34,034
But I have to be careful.

643
00:34:34,185 --> 00:34:35,819
If those Liberty Mutual
boys catch me

644
00:34:35,887 --> 00:34:39,156
while I'm out
for a quick jog,
it's all over.

645
00:34:39,223 --> 00:34:41,108
I can kiss
that million bucks good-bye

646
00:34:41,175 --> 00:34:43,160
and say hello
to Yuma State Prison.

647
00:34:43,227 --> 00:34:45,228
You could go to jail?

648
00:34:45,296 --> 00:34:46,763
Oh, yeah.

649
00:34:46,998 --> 00:34:48,916
But what's jail?

650
00:34:48,984 --> 00:34:53,320
As John Milton once said,
"The mind is its own place."

651
00:35:00,528 --> 00:35:01,428
So what do those, uh,

652
00:35:01,496 --> 00:35:03,196
Liberty Mutual boys
look like?

653
00:35:04,749 --> 00:35:05,883
Suits.

654
00:35:05,950 --> 00:35:07,718
Suits, huh?

655
00:35:08,969 --> 00:35:10,437
I'll make you a deal.

656
00:35:11,940 --> 00:35:14,942
You teach
me about imagination,

657
00:35:15,009 --> 00:35:17,010
and I'll keep a lookout.

658
00:35:17,078 --> 00:35:21,198
That might be asking
too much.

659
00:35:21,265 --> 00:35:25,568
I can pay you,
$34 and 18 cents in cash.

660
00:35:25,636 --> 00:35:27,204
I saved it up.

661
00:35:27,271 --> 00:35:28,505
[chuckles]

662
00:35:28,573 --> 00:35:31,208
And what exactly would
you want for your money?

663
00:35:31,275 --> 00:35:33,777
I wanna know
where stories come from.

664
00:35:34,079 --> 00:35:35,745
Ah...

665
00:35:35,813 --> 00:35:37,664
you want a mentor.

666
00:35:38,866 --> 00:35:40,334
A what?

667
00:35:40,402 --> 00:35:42,485
You absolutely sure
you want to set foot

668
00:35:42,553 --> 00:35:44,688
into such a mysterious realm?

669
00:35:44,756 --> 00:35:45,989
I'm sure.

670
00:35:46,056 --> 00:35:47,057
You may get lost in there

671
00:35:47,125 --> 00:35:48,975
and not be able to find
your way back.

672
00:35:49,311 --> 00:35:51,878
You said I'm fearless.

673
00:35:51,946 --> 00:35:53,329
That I did.

674
00:35:54,833 --> 00:35:56,583
So, we got a deal?

675
00:35:56,651 --> 00:35:57,884
My word is my bond.

676
00:35:57,952 --> 00:36:00,654
Great. So, when's
my first lesson?

677
00:36:00,722 --> 00:36:02,005
You just had it.

678
00:36:04,659 --> 00:36:06,627
Huh?

679
00:36:06,694 --> 00:36:08,128
I can't walk.

680
00:36:10,481 --> 00:36:11,882
What do you mean?

681
00:36:11,949 --> 00:36:15,335
I mean, I can't walk.
I just made up a story.

682
00:36:15,403 --> 00:36:17,370
Really?

683
00:36:17,438 --> 00:36:18,705
Really.

684
00:36:18,772 --> 00:36:21,124
You're kind of a jerk.

685
00:36:21,191 --> 00:36:23,576
Did you picture me running?

686
00:36:25,763 --> 00:36:27,164
Yeah.

687
00:36:27,232 --> 00:36:30,534
Did you see those men
in suits coming after me?

688
00:36:30,601 --> 00:36:32,719
Yeah.

689
00:36:32,786 --> 00:36:34,955
So did I.

690
00:36:35,022 --> 00:36:36,457
That's imagination.

691
00:36:39,310 --> 00:36:40,844
But you--

692
00:36:40,912 --> 00:36:42,012
Class dismissed.

693
00:36:42,280 --> 00:36:44,915
We'll have
another lesson tomorrow.

694
00:36:44,982 --> 00:36:47,417
Okay.

695
00:36:51,239 --> 00:36:53,624
I still think you're a jerk.

696
00:36:54,825 --> 00:36:56,426
Fair enough.

697
00:37:14,828 --> 00:37:16,713
Jubal McLaws.

698
00:37:19,834 --> 00:37:21,852
You got
my last Wildhorn there.

699
00:37:21,920 --> 00:37:23,437
It's gonna run you
35 cents.

700
00:37:23,505 --> 00:37:26,039
It's discounted
because it's missing
the last page.

701
00:37:26,107 --> 00:37:28,225
Somebody tore it right
out of the book.

702
00:37:28,292 --> 00:37:30,493
That's okay.
I'll take it.

703
00:37:36,084 --> 00:37:39,453
What would you say
if we extend a dinner
invitation this evening

704
00:37:39,520 --> 00:37:40,920
to our local author?

705
00:37:40,988 --> 00:37:42,989
Yes, Mama, please!
Oh, God.

706
00:37:43,057 --> 00:37:44,842
But he only eats
worms, Mama.

707
00:37:44,909 --> 00:37:46,877
Flora,

708
00:37:46,945 --> 00:37:48,444
Finn was just teasing you.

709
00:37:48,512 --> 00:37:49,879
I think it would be good
for you ladies

710
00:37:49,947 --> 00:37:51,398
to experience
a literary man.

711
00:37:51,466 --> 00:37:52,966
WILLOW: How do you expect
that to happen?

712
00:37:53,268 --> 00:37:54,084
He needs a ramp.

713
00:37:54,151 --> 00:37:55,936
We're not exactly
handicap-friendly.

714
00:37:56,004 --> 00:37:57,086
I'll build it.

715
00:37:57,154 --> 00:37:57,938
Thank you, Finn.

716
00:37:58,006 --> 00:37:59,289
Let me know
if I can help.

717
00:37:59,357 --> 00:38:01,875
[cell ring tone sounding]
It's Dad.

718
00:38:01,943 --> 00:38:03,760
Maybe he'd like
to come to dinner tonight.

719
00:38:03,827 --> 00:38:05,745
I wanna talk.

720
00:38:05,813 --> 00:38:07,647
After me. Hi, Dad.

721
00:38:07,715 --> 00:38:10,433
When am I gonna see you?

722
00:38:10,501 --> 00:38:12,335
Dad's coming the weekend
of Flora's birthday.

723
00:38:12,403 --> 00:38:13,570
Tell Dad he has
to finish my raft.

724
00:38:13,637 --> 00:38:15,071
When's the weekend
of my birthday, Mama?

725
00:38:15,139 --> 00:38:16,289
It's in August, baby.

726
00:38:16,357 --> 00:38:18,241
When's that?
Soon.

727
00:38:18,308 --> 00:38:20,043
Tell your father
I'll call him back.

728
00:38:20,110 --> 00:38:21,811
No, he wants
to talk to you now.

729
00:38:21,879 --> 00:38:24,331
Not while I'm driving.

730
00:38:24,499 --> 00:38:27,967
Today, I will introduce
our summer athletic program.

731
00:38:28,035 --> 00:38:30,754
The traditional game
of fetch,

732
00:38:30,821 --> 00:38:33,724
which I'm sure
you are familiar with.

733
00:38:33,791 --> 00:38:37,594
I hold in my hand
a Major League baseball.

734
00:38:37,729 --> 00:38:40,263
You might be interested
to know, sir,

735
00:38:40,330 --> 00:38:42,832
that before I lost
the use of my left arm,

736
00:38:42,900 --> 00:38:46,570
I was known to possess
a mean cut fast ball.

737
00:38:46,637 --> 00:38:49,973
Therefore, my affinity
for this wondrous sphere

738
00:38:50,041 --> 00:38:52,209
should come as no surprise.

739
00:38:53,945 --> 00:38:55,545
Fetch.

740
00:38:58,432 --> 00:39:01,150
I see the concept
of fetch eludes you.

741
00:39:02,386 --> 00:39:04,203
I blame Dave for that.

742
00:39:04,271 --> 00:39:08,208
For the record,
this will be the last time

743
00:39:08,276 --> 00:39:10,110
I fetch the ball.

744
00:39:12,130 --> 00:39:13,329
When do we start?

745
00:39:17,801 --> 00:39:18,835
Start what?

746
00:39:18,902 --> 00:39:20,119
My imagination.

747
00:39:20,187 --> 00:39:22,555
$34 and 18 cents.
It's all there.

748
00:39:22,623 --> 00:39:24,324
Uh, yeah.

749
00:39:26,077 --> 00:39:28,845
Well, no time
like the present.

750
00:39:30,714 --> 00:39:32,382
What do you see
up this street?

751
00:39:35,153 --> 00:39:37,287
Nothing.
Just a street.

752
00:39:39,290 --> 00:39:41,925
Okay, try telling me
what you don't see.

753
00:39:43,011 --> 00:39:44,077
Huh?

754
00:39:44,145 --> 00:39:46,380
What don't you see?

755
00:39:46,447 --> 00:39:47,197
I just told you.

756
00:39:47,265 --> 00:39:49,716
Work with me.

757
00:39:49,783 --> 00:39:51,284
See with
your mind's eye.

758
00:39:55,273 --> 00:39:57,807
Well, I sure don't see
no cowboy riding a horse.

759
00:39:57,875 --> 00:39:59,309
Well, if you're
looking for Jubal,

760
00:39:59,377 --> 00:40:00,844
you'll never see him.

761
00:40:00,911 --> 00:40:02,061
Why not?

762
00:40:02,129 --> 00:40:03,963
Gotta look
for your own things.

763
00:40:04,031 --> 00:40:05,431
How do I do that?

764
00:40:07,068 --> 00:40:08,334
Keep lookin'.

765
00:40:12,990 --> 00:40:14,541
I paid you.

766
00:40:14,609 --> 00:40:17,394
There's a mystery to
making things up, kiddo,

767
00:40:17,462 --> 00:40:20,497
and life offers
no guarantees.

768
00:40:20,564 --> 00:40:22,381
You got till
the end of the summer,

769
00:40:22,449 --> 00:40:23,850
or I want my money back.

770
00:40:25,252 --> 00:40:26,519
Well, I've always
done my best

771
00:40:26,588 --> 00:40:28,655
when working
under a deadline.

772
00:40:34,445 --> 00:40:36,062
You're invited over
for dinner tonight,

773
00:40:36,130 --> 00:40:37,330
precisely at 7:00.

774
00:40:41,051 --> 00:40:42,886
Oh, dear.

775
00:40:48,692 --> 00:40:49,742
Hey, Finn.

776
00:40:49,810 --> 00:40:51,661
Oh, hi, Carl.

777
00:40:53,997 --> 00:40:55,998
I'm not Carl.

778
00:40:56,066 --> 00:40:57,867
I'm Diego Santana...

779
00:40:59,136 --> 00:41:01,304
train robber
and faithful sidekick.

780
00:41:01,371 --> 00:41:03,139
Whose sidekick?

781
00:41:03,207 --> 00:41:05,191
The man at Dog Dave's.

782
00:41:05,259 --> 00:41:07,293
What are you doing?

783
00:41:07,361 --> 00:41:08,895
Building a ramp for Monte.

784
00:41:08,963 --> 00:41:10,213
Who's Monte?

785
00:41:10,281 --> 00:41:11,881
The man at Dog Dave's.

786
00:41:11,949 --> 00:41:13,533
I'm his sidekick.

787
00:41:13,601 --> 00:41:16,002
Good, then you can
help me build this.

788
00:41:16,069 --> 00:41:17,336
I can do that.

789
00:41:17,404 --> 00:41:19,405
[telephone rings,
machine beeps]

790
00:41:19,473 --> 00:41:21,524
Hey, Uncle Monte.
It's Henry.

791
00:41:21,759 --> 00:41:23,794
Just calling to see
how that whole killing
yourself thing

792
00:41:23,861 --> 00:41:25,228
is working out for you.

793
00:41:27,364 --> 00:41:31,167
It's temporarily postponed.

794
00:41:31,436 --> 00:41:33,553
Oh. Well,
the summer's young.

795
00:41:33,621 --> 00:41:37,390
An invitation has been
extended for dinner.

796
00:41:37,458 --> 00:41:39,176
Next door.

797
00:41:39,243 --> 00:41:41,445
I've accepted.

798
00:41:41,512 --> 00:41:43,146
What, the beautiful woman
from the roof?

799
00:41:43,214 --> 00:41:43,996
The very same.

800
00:41:44,064 --> 00:41:45,982
Well, that's great!

801
00:41:46,050 --> 00:41:46,750
You know what to do?

802
00:41:46,818 --> 00:41:47,851
Eat?

803
00:41:47,919 --> 00:41:49,802
Just bring her something nice.

804
00:41:49,870 --> 00:41:50,453
Pick some flowers.

805
00:41:50,521 --> 00:41:52,104
Too conventional.

806
00:41:52,172 --> 00:41:53,873
Well, you'll figure it out.

807
00:41:53,941 --> 00:41:56,893
I'm guessing you didn't
call Joe Viola back.

808
00:41:56,961 --> 00:41:58,344
Correct.

809
00:41:58,412 --> 00:42:00,129
Why don't you just listen
to what he has to say?

810
00:42:00,197 --> 00:42:01,514
Not interested.

811
00:42:01,582 --> 00:42:03,366
You take care
of yourself, Uncle Monte.

812
00:42:03,434 --> 00:42:05,251
Not interested.

813
00:42:05,319 --> 00:42:07,019
Okay, bye, Uncle Monte.

814
00:42:07,087 --> 00:42:09,705
Bye, young Henry.

815
00:42:45,075 --> 00:42:47,377
Oh.

816
00:42:47,444 --> 00:42:50,864
As I recall, it's improper
to arrive empty-handed.

817
00:42:50,932 --> 00:42:52,014
A mirror?

818
00:42:52,082 --> 00:42:53,115
I figure a house
full of ladies

819
00:42:53,183 --> 00:42:54,934
could always
use another one.

820
00:42:55,002 --> 00:42:56,403
Well, thank you.

821
00:42:56,470 --> 00:42:58,004
This is quite
a unique gift.

822
00:43:00,374 --> 00:43:01,441
Do come in,
Mr. Wildhorn.

823
00:43:01,508 --> 00:43:02,725
Thank you.

824
00:43:04,011 --> 00:43:06,129
I didn't think you'd mind
if Spot came along.

825
00:43:06,196 --> 00:43:07,330
He's always welcome.

826
00:43:07,398 --> 00:43:10,066
May I take your hat,
Mr. Wildhorn?

827
00:43:10,134 --> 00:43:11,535
Why, thank you, Flora.

828
00:43:11,602 --> 00:43:15,138
Ladies, please see
Mr. Wildhorn to the table.

829
00:43:15,206 --> 00:43:16,656
I hope you like chicken.

830
00:43:16,724 --> 00:43:18,758
Never had a chicken
do me wrong.

831
00:43:18,959 --> 00:43:20,976
Finn tells me
you write books.

832
00:43:21,044 --> 00:43:22,778
It's been a while.

833
00:43:22,846 --> 00:43:25,415
No texting at the table,
okay, Willow?

834
00:43:25,482 --> 00:43:28,284
I always felt
like a book is...

835
00:43:28,352 --> 00:43:31,254
a friend that does
what no friend can do.

836
00:43:31,322 --> 00:43:33,373
Stay quiet when you wanna think.

837
00:43:33,440 --> 00:43:35,559
[chuckles]

838
00:43:35,626 --> 00:43:37,844
Would you care for
some wine, Mr. Wildhorn?

839
00:43:37,912 --> 00:43:40,814
Ordinarily, I don't indulge,
Mrs. O'Neil,

840
00:43:40,881 --> 00:43:44,184
but since I may
work my way up to a toast,

841
00:43:44,252 --> 00:43:45,451
I think maybe
a glass of wine

842
00:43:45,519 --> 00:43:47,788
might be in order,
just this once.

843
00:43:47,855 --> 00:43:50,073
You'll have to excuse me
if I don't get up.

844
00:43:50,141 --> 00:43:53,276
I started
reading The Saga
of Jubal McLaws.

845
00:43:53,544 --> 00:43:54,578
It's really cool.

846
00:43:54,645 --> 00:43:57,914
Oh, one
of my kinder reviews.

847
00:43:57,982 --> 00:43:59,516
I got it cheap
'cause it didn't have
the last page.

848
00:43:59,750 --> 00:44:01,400
Oh, you're not missing much.

849
00:44:01,468 --> 00:44:04,370
I always meant to rewrite
that page anyway.

850
00:44:04,438 --> 00:44:06,239
Are all your books
about the West?

851
00:44:06,307 --> 00:44:07,857
Pretty much.

852
00:44:08,059 --> 00:44:11,344
I love horses. I used
to ride when I was a child.

853
00:44:11,412 --> 00:44:13,296
Can you pass the gravy,
please?

854
00:44:13,363 --> 00:44:15,214
Good horse
is half the dream.

855
00:44:15,282 --> 00:44:17,383
What's the other half?

856
00:44:17,451 --> 00:44:20,170
Your knight in shining armor.

857
00:44:22,523 --> 00:44:24,307
Do you know any stories
about elephants?

858
00:44:24,374 --> 00:44:26,610
Flora loves elephants.

859
00:44:26,677 --> 00:44:28,444
I'm afraid I'm not
a reliable source

860
00:44:28,512 --> 00:44:30,730
when it comes
to pachyderms.

861
00:44:32,049 --> 00:44:34,150
How did Jubal come to be
the man who rides alone?

862
00:44:34,218 --> 00:44:36,970
He didn't have much choice.

863
00:44:39,390 --> 00:44:41,057
The end of the Civil War,

864
00:44:41,125 --> 00:44:44,627
Jubal rode home to Texas
to be reunited with his family.

865
00:44:44,695 --> 00:44:45,795
It took
a good many years

866
00:44:45,862 --> 00:44:47,614
before he
could bring himself

867
00:44:47,681 --> 00:44:49,048
to mention
the ghastly sight
that awaited him

868
00:44:49,116 --> 00:44:51,518
when he arrived back
at the old homestead.

869
00:44:51,585 --> 00:44:52,769
What happened?

870
00:44:52,836 --> 00:44:55,505
Comanche raiding party.

871
00:44:55,573 --> 00:44:58,575
His papa's horse
had been gut shot,

872
00:44:58,642 --> 00:45:01,645
pin-cushioned with arrows
and left to suffer.

873
00:45:01,712 --> 00:45:03,863
He found
his beloved mother

874
00:45:03,931 --> 00:45:07,049
outside the cabin,
her head nearly severed,

875
00:45:07,117 --> 00:45:08,818
her stomach ripped open.

876
00:45:08,886 --> 00:45:10,737
Remember, girls,
it's just a story.

877
00:45:10,804 --> 00:45:12,071
Just a story?

878
00:45:12,139 --> 00:45:14,723
I only meant
that it didn't really happen.

879
00:45:14,959 --> 00:45:18,161
It happened to Jubal.

880
00:45:21,399 --> 00:45:23,216
Mashed potatoes, Mr. Wildhorn?

881
00:45:25,169 --> 00:45:29,021
MONTE: Sweet old place
you've got here, Mrs. O'Neil.

882
00:45:29,090 --> 00:45:32,324
Belonged to my grandparents,
then my mom.

883
00:45:32,392 --> 00:45:34,126
I spent my summers here
growing up.

884
00:45:34,194 --> 00:45:36,179
Well, I prefer growing up
in the city,

885
00:45:36,246 --> 00:45:38,782
but instead,
I'm being held prisoner here.

886
00:45:41,185 --> 00:45:43,286
Are you ready
for my three words, Mama?

887
00:45:43,353 --> 00:45:45,588
If you're prepared.

888
00:45:45,656 --> 00:45:47,490
Can I be excused?

889
00:45:47,558 --> 00:45:50,009
You may not.
Go ahead, Finn.

890
00:45:50,077 --> 00:45:52,078
One, imagination:

891
00:45:52,146 --> 00:45:54,647
the process of forming
a mental image of something

892
00:45:54,715 --> 00:45:57,917
never before perceived
by the imaginer in reality.

893
00:45:57,985 --> 00:46:00,770
Besides being
the most powerful force

894
00:46:00,838 --> 00:46:03,406
ever made available
for humankind.

895
00:46:03,474 --> 00:46:05,258
Two,

896
00:46:05,326 --> 00:46:06,909
bamboozle:

897
00:46:06,977 --> 00:46:09,479
to deceive or get the better
of somebody by trickery.

898
00:46:09,547 --> 00:46:12,165
Cheat, fleece, or snooker.

899
00:46:12,233 --> 00:46:13,148
[laughs]

900
00:46:13,467 --> 00:46:15,334
And your third word?

901
00:46:15,636 --> 00:46:17,687
Mentor:

902
00:46:17,754 --> 00:46:21,891
a trusted counselor
or guide, tutor or coach.

903
00:46:23,777 --> 00:46:25,995
Interesting choices.

904
00:46:26,063 --> 00:46:28,564
I'm gonna be seven
this summer.

905
00:46:28,632 --> 00:46:29,699
You can
come to my party.

906
00:46:29,766 --> 00:46:31,451
Flora, he doesn't want to.

907
00:46:31,518 --> 00:46:33,820
Finnegan.
It's August 15th.

908
00:46:33,888 --> 00:46:35,354
And you're under
no obligation.

909
00:46:35,422 --> 00:46:37,824
To the contrary.

910
00:46:37,892 --> 00:46:39,893
I greatly appreciate
being included

911
00:46:39,960 --> 00:46:42,028
in your celebratory plans

912
00:46:42,095 --> 00:46:45,731
and I will be sure to mark
that special day on my calendar.

913
00:46:48,418 --> 00:46:50,053
Who plays the piano?

914
00:46:50,121 --> 00:46:52,938
I've been trying
to teach these three,
to no avail.

915
00:46:53,007 --> 00:46:55,492
Do you appreciate music,
Mr. Wildhorn?

916
00:46:55,559 --> 00:46:57,477
Oh, yes, ma'am, I do.

917
00:46:57,545 --> 00:47:01,914
In my younger days, I was often
complimented for my voice.

918
00:47:01,982 --> 00:47:04,384
Would you like
to sing for us?

919
00:47:04,452 --> 00:47:06,586
It's the least I can do.

920
00:47:06,653 --> 00:47:08,421
Now may I be excused?

921
00:47:08,488 --> 00:47:12,125
No. Mr. Wildhorn's
going to favor us with a song.

922
00:47:13,043 --> 00:47:15,978
¶ Oh, a captain
born in Halifax ¶

923
00:47:16,046 --> 00:47:18,114
¶ Who dwelt
in country quarters ¶

924
00:47:18,182 --> 00:47:19,899
¶ Seduced a maid
who hanged herself ¶

925
00:47:19,967 --> 00:47:21,734
¶ Next morning
in her garters ¶

926
00:47:21,802 --> 00:47:22,835
I don't think
I know that one.

927
00:47:23,037 --> 00:47:26,238
Well, okay...
play something you do know.

928
00:47:28,342 --> 00:47:31,560
Um, well...

929
00:47:31,829 --> 00:47:33,563
it's not a song, exactly.

930
00:47:33,631 --> 00:47:36,666
But...here goes.

931
00:47:37,901 --> 00:47:41,154
[playing Beethoven's
Pathetique Sonata]

932
00:48:14,788 --> 00:48:17,774
Mmm, I would leave
all my windows open

933
00:48:17,841 --> 00:48:20,242
to hear that kind of playing.

934
00:48:20,311 --> 00:48:24,830
That would be
one of my kinder reviews.

935
00:48:24,898 --> 00:48:26,699
[Spot barking]

936
00:48:26,767 --> 00:48:29,918
He's telling me
I've outstayed my welcome.

937
00:48:30,154 --> 00:48:33,122
All right, girls. Let's say
good night to Mr. Wildhorn.

938
00:48:34,792 --> 00:48:36,759
Good night, Monte.

939
00:48:36,827 --> 00:48:38,093
Oh, good night, Flora.

940
00:48:40,197 --> 00:48:41,764
I'll be ready first thing
in the morning.

941
00:48:41,832 --> 00:48:43,399
For what?

942
00:48:43,467 --> 00:48:45,000
You know.

943
00:48:45,068 --> 00:48:46,669
Oh, oh, oh. All right.

944
00:48:46,737 --> 00:48:48,705
Yeah, thanks
for the reminder.

945
00:48:50,106 --> 00:48:52,509
Girls, you can
clear the table.
You too, Willow.

946
00:48:55,645 --> 00:48:57,313
Mrs. O'Neil,

947
00:48:57,414 --> 00:49:00,483
I want to thank you
for a very lovely evening.

948
00:49:00,550 --> 00:49:01,984
I don't believe I have ever

949
00:49:02,052 --> 00:49:03,803
heard Beethoven's
Pathetique Sonata

950
00:49:03,870 --> 00:49:05,805
played with such affection.

951
00:49:05,873 --> 00:49:07,857
You know the piece.

952
00:49:07,924 --> 00:49:10,426
Well, when I was writing,

953
00:49:10,494 --> 00:49:12,545
I listened
to all kinds of music.

954
00:49:16,900 --> 00:49:18,467
Mr. Wildhorn.

955
00:49:22,839 --> 00:49:27,026
Why did you stop writing?

956
00:49:27,093 --> 00:49:30,145
Same reason
I gave up religion.

957
00:49:30,213 --> 00:49:34,166
God confided in me
that he's an atheist.

958
00:49:36,186 --> 00:49:39,121
Did your Jubal McLaws
ever love a woman?

959
00:49:41,191 --> 00:49:43,158
Well, Jubal
always got the girl,

960
00:49:43,226 --> 00:49:47,430
but he only
fell in love once.

961
00:49:47,498 --> 00:49:49,899
That's more than some.

962
00:49:49,966 --> 00:49:52,268
Did they live
happily ever after?

963
00:49:52,335 --> 00:49:53,903
No.

964
00:49:54,104 --> 00:49:58,324
He lost her
to the influenza
in Cattle Wars.

965
00:49:58,391 --> 00:50:01,410
And he never fell in love
after that?

966
00:50:03,630 --> 00:50:05,964
How could he?

967
00:50:08,218 --> 00:50:12,555
I think Jubal
has quite a hold on you.

968
00:50:12,623 --> 00:50:19,161
Well, all the things
I couldn't do
in the real world,

969
00:50:19,229 --> 00:50:21,430
Jubal let me do
on the page.

970
00:50:24,568 --> 00:50:26,502
Good night, Mrs. O'Neil.

971
00:50:26,570 --> 00:50:28,537
Thanks for
the chicken dinner.

972
00:50:33,961 --> 00:50:36,412
You owe me a toast,
Mr. Wildhorn.

973
00:50:36,479 --> 00:50:38,247
I'm good for it.

974
00:50:44,071 --> 00:50:46,606
Your behavior tonight
was exemplary.

975
00:50:46,674 --> 00:50:50,510
As a result, I'm going to
lift the ban on farting.

976
00:50:52,913 --> 00:50:55,297
¶ A captain
born in Halifax ¶

977
00:50:55,365 --> 00:50:57,249
¶ Who dwelt
in country quarters ¶

978
00:50:57,317 --> 00:50:59,135
¶ Seduced a maid
who hanged herself¶

979
00:50:59,203 --> 00:51:02,138
¶ One morning
in her garters ¶

980
00:51:03,591 --> 00:51:04,424
Fetch.

981
00:51:06,293 --> 00:51:09,945
Maybe it's the word "fetch"
that doesn't resonate.

982
00:51:10,014 --> 00:51:13,249
Perhaps "retrieve"
will stimulate

983
00:51:13,317 --> 00:51:16,452
some long-dormant instinct.

984
00:51:16,520 --> 00:51:19,188
Retrieve.

985
00:51:19,256 --> 00:51:21,857
Retrieve.

986
00:51:26,329 --> 00:51:28,264
FINN: It still just
looks like a street.

987
00:51:32,018 --> 00:51:33,519
You're holding back.

988
00:51:33,587 --> 00:51:36,439
I'm not.

989
00:51:36,507 --> 00:51:37,540
I can't do this.

990
00:51:37,607 --> 00:51:39,359
It's not what I hear.

991
00:51:40,494 --> 00:51:41,694
What?

992
00:51:41,962 --> 00:51:45,481
Well, word about town
is that I'm known

993
00:51:45,549 --> 00:51:49,218
to consider earthworm
something of a delicacy.

994
00:51:51,738 --> 00:51:52,738
Where did--?

995
00:51:52,806 --> 00:51:54,223
I have my sources.

996
00:51:54,391 --> 00:51:57,009
But I didn't know you then.
You know, I was just--

997
00:51:57,144 --> 00:51:59,144
Using your imagination.

998
00:52:56,286 --> 00:52:58,337
[telephone rings]

999
00:52:58,405 --> 00:53:00,139
Hello?

1000
00:53:00,206 --> 00:53:02,608
Hi. This is Monte Wildhorn.

1001
00:53:02,675 --> 00:53:04,076
Oh, hi, Monte?

1002
00:53:04,144 --> 00:53:05,161
Is your boy there?

1003
00:53:05,229 --> 00:53:06,912
The boy?

1004
00:53:06,980 --> 00:53:09,565
Oh. Oh. Hold on.
Hold on.

1005
00:53:09,632 --> 00:53:11,250
Carl! It's the phone.

1006
00:53:11,318 --> 00:53:13,252
The phone!
What is it, Mom?

1007
00:53:13,320 --> 00:53:15,454
It's a phone call,
for you.

1008
00:53:15,522 --> 00:53:17,423
It is? Who is it?

1009
00:53:17,491 --> 00:53:18,741
Well, find out.

1010
00:53:18,809 --> 00:53:21,093
This is Carl Loop.

1011
00:53:21,161 --> 00:53:23,829
Oh. I must have
the wrong number.

1012
00:53:23,897 --> 00:53:25,998
I was looking
for Diego Santana.

1013
00:53:26,065 --> 00:53:28,801
I'm Diego Santana.

1014
00:53:28,869 --> 00:53:30,470
All right, then.

1015
00:53:30,537 --> 00:53:34,122
Saddle up, amigo.
We're riding into town.

1016
00:53:34,190 --> 00:53:37,426
Mom, we're riding
into town.

1017
00:53:37,494 --> 00:53:42,481
[music playing]

1018
00:53:42,549 --> 00:53:44,483
Do you always wear
a white hat?

1019
00:53:45,985 --> 00:53:48,320
I wear
a white hat, Diego,

1020
00:53:48,388 --> 00:53:50,523
so the folks
can tell the good guys

1021
00:53:50,590 --> 00:53:53,292
from the bad guys
in case of gun play.

1022
00:53:56,063 --> 00:53:57,196
What's with the goggles?

1023
00:53:57,264 --> 00:53:59,131
Then no one
knows I'm Carl.

1024
00:54:00,467 --> 00:54:02,101
Good thinking.

1025
00:54:08,492 --> 00:54:10,025
Now if you'll
be kind enough

1026
00:54:10,093 --> 00:54:13,078
to slide the case
of spirits on to my lap,

1027
00:54:13,146 --> 00:54:15,180
this business
will be concluded,

1028
00:54:15,249 --> 00:54:18,351
and we can catch up
on each other's personal lives.

1029
00:54:18,418 --> 00:54:20,553
I would be looking
forward to it.

1030
00:54:24,407 --> 00:54:26,342
What happened to the Slim Jims?

1031
00:54:28,528 --> 00:54:30,679
What's your income
this year, Monte?

1032
00:54:30,747 --> 00:54:35,450
I estimate my gross income
at $34 and 18 cents.

1033
00:54:35,518 --> 00:54:38,888
A good portion of which
I've invested with Mahmoud.

1034
00:54:38,955 --> 00:54:42,491
Sometimes I wanna
pull my pants down.

1035
00:54:42,559 --> 00:54:44,493
Join the club.

1036
00:54:56,173 --> 00:54:58,207
You gonna drink all that?

1037
00:55:00,077 --> 00:55:02,778
I have every intention
of doing so.

1038
00:55:02,845 --> 00:55:04,080
Why?

1039
00:55:05,848 --> 00:55:08,784
'Cause I'm a drunk,
and that's what we do.

1040
00:55:13,190 --> 00:55:15,724
Get drunk enough,
you'll cry over anything.

1041
00:55:17,461 --> 00:55:20,796
Real tears are a useful way
of getting to a place.

1042
00:55:22,632 --> 00:55:23,865
What place?

1043
00:55:23,933 --> 00:55:25,501
Anywhere you need to go.

1044
00:55:26,936 --> 00:55:29,371
Now look out
there and tell me
what's not there,

1045
00:55:29,439 --> 00:55:31,207
and make me interested.

1046
00:55:35,512 --> 00:55:36,712
I see...

1047
00:55:39,015 --> 00:55:40,682
I see...

1048
00:55:43,287 --> 00:55:45,855
a girl
walking by the lake.

1049
00:55:45,922 --> 00:55:47,122
How old is she?

1050
00:55:47,190 --> 00:55:48,691
What does she look like?
What is she wearing?

1051
00:55:50,276 --> 00:55:52,678
She's ten years old,
and she's got a ponytail.

1052
00:55:52,746 --> 00:55:54,363
What's she doing?

1053
00:55:54,431 --> 00:55:57,432
She's looking
behind her.

1054
00:55:57,500 --> 00:55:59,519
Why?

1055
00:55:59,586 --> 00:56:02,521
'Cause there's
a man following her.

1056
00:56:04,107 --> 00:56:05,140
So what does she do?

1057
00:56:05,208 --> 00:56:06,909
She starts running.

1058
00:56:06,977 --> 00:56:08,710
He chases her.

1059
00:56:08,778 --> 00:56:09,996
Does he catch her?

1060
00:56:10,063 --> 00:56:12,080
No.

1061
00:56:12,148 --> 00:56:13,866
She gets away.

1062
00:56:13,934 --> 00:56:15,434
How?

1063
00:56:15,501 --> 00:56:16,518
She runs to her neighbor,
Al Kaiser's house

1064
00:56:16,586 --> 00:56:18,254
and disappears
around the back.

1065
00:56:18,488 --> 00:56:19,855
When the bad guy
gets there,

1066
00:56:19,923 --> 00:56:21,974
all he sees is one of
her sneakers lying in front

1067
00:56:22,041 --> 00:56:23,976
of an open door that leads
down to the cellar.

1068
00:56:24,043 --> 00:56:26,546
When the bad guys goes down
the stairs to grab her,

1069
00:56:26,613 --> 00:56:28,230
she jumps out from
behind the big oak tree

1070
00:56:28,298 --> 00:56:29,998
where she's been hiding
and lifts

1071
00:56:30,066 --> 00:56:31,200
that heavy door
off the ground

1072
00:56:31,267 --> 00:56:32,567
and closes it
on top of him,

1073
00:56:32,669 --> 00:56:33,752
and before
he can escape,

1074
00:56:33,921 --> 00:56:36,088
she grabs
the rake Al Kaiser
keeps by the door

1075
00:56:36,156 --> 00:56:37,289
and slides it
through the handles,

1076
00:56:37,357 --> 00:56:38,557
which traps the bad guy

1077
00:56:38,625 --> 00:56:40,492
until the cops
come to take him away.

1078
00:56:43,130 --> 00:56:45,464
Congratulations.

1079
00:56:45,531 --> 00:56:47,532
You just made up
your first story.

1080
00:56:47,768 --> 00:56:49,485
I know,
'cause Carl Loop and me,

1081
00:56:49,552 --> 00:56:50,886
we always used
to hide there

1082
00:56:50,954 --> 00:56:51,954
when we didn't
want our mothers

1083
00:56:52,022 --> 00:56:53,222
to know where we were.

1084
00:56:54,241 --> 00:56:56,191
Good instincts.

1085
00:56:56,259 --> 00:56:58,026
You draw from
your own experiences.

1086
00:56:58,094 --> 00:56:59,929
Now what?

1087
00:57:01,448 --> 00:57:03,249
You work me too hard.

1088
00:57:03,317 --> 00:57:04,616
Class dismissed.

1089
00:57:05,919 --> 00:57:07,853
Okay. See ya.

1090
00:57:09,972 --> 00:57:12,574
Hey, Mom, Mom!
I wrote a story!

1091
00:57:12,642 --> 00:57:13,909
I wrote a story!

1092
00:57:16,579 --> 00:57:18,813
I'm one hell of a mentor.

1093
00:58:30,037 --> 00:58:35,758
Monte, you know
that dancehall gal, Miss Gussy?

1094
00:58:35,826 --> 00:58:38,160
The one that runs
the saloon in all your books?

1095
00:58:38,227 --> 00:58:39,795
I do.

1096
00:58:39,863 --> 00:58:43,566
I'm surprised she and Jubal
never got together.

1097
00:58:45,201 --> 00:58:48,170
Tell you the truth,
I was surprised too.

1098
00:58:48,237 --> 00:58:50,940
But then, who among us

1099
00:58:51,007 --> 00:58:52,575
truly knows the ways
of love?

1100
00:58:54,143 --> 00:58:56,078
You got that right, sir.

1101
00:58:56,145 --> 00:58:58,180
Mama.
Yes?

1102
00:58:58,247 --> 00:58:59,865
I don't wanna paint anymore.

1103
00:58:59,933 --> 00:59:02,401
Okay, birthday girl.
What do you wanna do?

1104
00:59:02,468 --> 00:59:03,585
I wanna go jump.

1105
00:59:03,653 --> 00:59:04,820
Go jump.

1106
00:59:04,887 --> 00:59:08,890
However, we cannot leave
Mr. Wildhorn half done.

1107
00:59:08,959 --> 00:59:10,225
Thank you.

1108
00:59:10,493 --> 00:59:12,077
Listen, lady, I gotta be
outta here by 3:00.

1109
00:59:12,145 --> 00:59:14,379
It was my understanding
I had you for the entire day.

1110
00:59:14,447 --> 00:59:15,480
Yeah, well,
I got a 4:00

1111
00:59:15,548 --> 00:59:17,399
on the other side
of the lake.

1112
00:59:17,466 --> 00:59:20,119
[scoffs]

1113
00:59:22,806 --> 00:59:24,957
Mama, look
what I made for Flora.

1114
00:59:25,024 --> 00:59:26,192
I'm testing it for her.

1115
00:59:26,259 --> 00:59:28,076
Oh, okay.
Take it easy with that.

1116
00:59:28,144 --> 00:59:29,462
Be careful with that,
Finn, okay?

1117
00:59:29,529 --> 00:59:31,029
I don't wanna see
any one-eyed daughters.

1118
00:59:31,098 --> 00:59:32,364
Okay.

1119
00:59:32,599 --> 00:59:34,399
[cell ring tone sounding]

1120
00:59:34,467 --> 00:59:36,401
Oh, excuse me.

1121
00:59:37,953 --> 00:59:40,906
Jack, where are you?
It started over an hour ago.

1122
00:59:45,628 --> 00:59:47,929
All right, hang on.

1123
00:59:47,997 --> 00:59:51,800
Hey, Flora. Hey, honey.
It's Daddy for you.

1124
00:59:51,868 --> 00:59:53,101
Yay.

1125
01:00:01,478 --> 01:00:02,611
He's not coming.

1126
01:00:05,649 --> 01:00:07,949
I don't know why
I'm always surprised.

1127
01:00:09,752 --> 01:00:11,187
I just...

1128
01:00:11,254 --> 01:00:13,922
I guess I keep hoping
for the sake of the girls.

1129
01:00:18,361 --> 01:00:19,928
Daddy's not coming.

1130
01:00:22,415 --> 01:00:25,066
Oh, hey, baby girl,
let's go jump.

1131
01:00:25,134 --> 01:00:27,336
I don't wanna jump.

1132
01:00:28,855 --> 01:00:31,440
Dad said it would
be okay if I came up
to stay with him.

1133
01:00:31,507 --> 01:00:33,458
Willow, we are not
doing this again.

1134
01:00:33,526 --> 01:00:34,827
There's nothing
for me to do here.

1135
01:00:34,895 --> 01:00:36,295
All my friends
are in the city.

1136
01:00:36,362 --> 01:00:37,729
You know,
he can't even show up

1137
01:00:37,797 --> 01:00:39,231
for his own daughter's
birthday party.

1138
01:00:39,499 --> 01:00:41,850
Maybe he just didn't
want to see you.

1139
01:00:41,918 --> 01:00:43,051
That's enough.

1140
01:00:54,914 --> 01:00:58,317
Why don't I just go and talk
to Flora for a minute?

1141
01:00:59,268 --> 01:01:00,685
Okay.

1142
01:01:03,106 --> 01:01:05,541
I'm looking for
the birthday girl.

1143
01:01:05,742 --> 01:01:07,659
You know where
I can find her?

1144
01:01:08,445 --> 01:01:10,262
I'm the birthday girl.

1145
01:01:10,329 --> 01:01:11,947
Oh, good.

1146
01:01:12,015 --> 01:01:14,449
'Cause I got
something for you.

1147
01:01:14,517 --> 01:01:16,218
What is it?

1148
01:01:16,286 --> 01:01:17,652
It's your birthday present.

1149
01:01:17,720 --> 01:01:19,804
I think it's here.
Where'd I put it?

1150
01:01:19,872 --> 01:01:21,973
Ah, there it is.

1151
01:01:22,042 --> 01:01:23,308
Happy birthday.

1152
01:01:23,543 --> 01:01:25,310
What is it?

1153
01:01:25,378 --> 01:01:26,311
It's a story.

1154
01:01:26,379 --> 01:01:27,696
About what?

1155
01:01:27,764 --> 01:01:30,115
About an elephant
named Tony.

1156
01:01:31,634 --> 01:01:32,685
Well, he said he was
a friend of yours,

1157
01:01:32,752 --> 01:01:36,288
and he asked me
to write it down for him.

1158
01:01:36,356 --> 01:01:37,706
Is Tony a real elephant?

1159
01:01:37,974 --> 01:01:39,558
Yes, ma'am, he sure is.

1160
01:01:39,625 --> 01:01:41,677
Thank you so much!

1161
01:01:41,745 --> 01:01:44,013
Mom! Look what I got!

1162
01:01:52,355 --> 01:01:54,606
Man, that is one hot lady.

1163
01:01:54,674 --> 01:01:58,494
If she was my woman,
I'd never let her leave the bed.

1164
01:01:58,561 --> 01:02:00,863
You know
what I'm talking about.

1165
01:02:04,050 --> 01:02:05,184
Time to go to work.

1166
01:02:05,252 --> 01:02:07,186
Hey, you like magic tricks?
I'll do one for ya.

1167
01:02:07,254 --> 01:02:09,755
Can you make yourself
disappear, Mr. Clown?

1168
01:02:09,823 --> 01:02:12,925
Don't call me "Mr. Clown."

1169
01:02:12,992 --> 01:02:14,593
I happen
to be The Amazing Ted.

1170
01:02:14,661 --> 01:02:16,661
Whatever you say,
Mr. Clown.

1171
01:02:18,147 --> 01:02:19,080
Asshole.

1172
01:02:19,148 --> 01:02:20,616
You got my name right.

1173
01:02:20,684 --> 01:02:22,067
It's magic time!

1174
01:02:22,135 --> 01:02:25,954
Hey! Come on, kids.
Gather 'round.

1175
01:02:26,022 --> 01:02:27,922
Magic time!

1176
01:02:27,990 --> 01:02:29,374
[laughing]

1177
01:02:29,442 --> 01:02:30,876
Pay close attention,

1178
01:02:31,077 --> 01:02:35,030
because at no point
do my hands ever leave my arms.

1179
01:02:35,097 --> 01:02:36,898
Huh? [laughs]

1180
01:02:36,966 --> 01:02:40,235
Now who here likes rabbits?

1181
01:02:40,303 --> 01:02:41,970
KIDS: I do!

1182
01:02:43,272 --> 01:02:44,440
[loud popping]

1183
01:02:44,507 --> 01:02:45,290
[air hissing]

1184
01:02:45,358 --> 01:02:46,374
It slipped.

1185
01:02:46,543 --> 01:02:48,360
CLOWN: Son of a bitch!

1186
01:02:48,427 --> 01:02:51,179
Hey! Hey!
You spoiled little brat!

1187
01:02:51,247 --> 01:02:53,749
Hey! That castle's
how I make my living.

1188
01:02:53,817 --> 01:02:55,968
Jesus Christ!
Help, Mom!

1189
01:02:56,036 --> 01:02:58,837
Everybody get away from there
before you make it worse!

1190
01:02:58,905 --> 01:03:00,972
Somebody get
that fat kid outta there!

1191
01:03:01,040 --> 01:03:03,508
What the hell's he doing
in there in the first place?

1192
01:03:03,576 --> 01:03:06,545
It's for little kids.
He weighs, like, 900 pounds!

1193
01:03:06,612 --> 01:03:08,013
Let me tell you something.

1194
01:03:08,081 --> 01:03:09,364
You haven't heard
the last of this.

1195
01:03:09,432 --> 01:03:10,632
I got stuck.

1196
01:03:10,700 --> 01:03:12,251
You don't think
clowns have lawyers?

1197
01:03:12,318 --> 01:03:13,819
You better think again,

1198
01:03:13,887 --> 01:03:15,504
'cause you're about to be
hearing from my lawyer.

1199
01:03:15,572 --> 01:03:16,989
[gunshot]

1200
01:03:19,959 --> 01:03:23,278
Reach for the sky,
you mud-sucking

1201
01:03:23,345 --> 01:03:24,262
yellow sidewinder.

1202
01:03:24,330 --> 01:03:25,547
All right, Jesus.

1203
01:03:25,615 --> 01:03:27,115
Easy, man.
Shit, don't shoot.

1204
01:03:27,183 --> 01:03:29,334
I'm so gonna hear from
the parents on this one.

1205
01:03:29,402 --> 01:03:31,286
The Amazing Ted,

1206
01:03:31,353 --> 01:03:33,038
or Mr. Clown?

1207
01:03:33,106 --> 01:03:36,341
Which do you prefer
on your tombstone?

1208
01:03:36,476 --> 01:03:38,960
Oh, tombstones?
Why's he talking
about tombstones?

1209
01:03:39,028 --> 01:03:41,663
If you wanna continue
your useless existence,

1210
01:03:41,898 --> 01:03:43,848
I strongly urge
a sincere apology

1211
01:03:43,916 --> 01:03:45,283
to Miss Finnegan O'Neil.

1212
01:03:45,551 --> 01:03:47,803
Okay. Okay.

1213
01:03:47,870 --> 01:03:50,556
I'm sorry.
I'm really,
really sorry.

1214
01:03:50,623 --> 01:03:52,691
Apology accepted.

1215
01:03:52,758 --> 01:03:54,510
Now, git!

1216
01:03:54,577 --> 01:03:56,678
Oh!

1217
01:03:56,745 --> 01:03:59,647
Well, birthday cake, anyone?

1218
01:03:59,715 --> 01:04:01,849
KIDS: Me!

1219
01:04:04,988 --> 01:04:06,738
Did you have fun today?

1220
01:04:06,806 --> 01:04:09,340
I liked it when
Monte shot my clown.

1221
01:04:09,408 --> 01:04:11,010
Oh, well, baby,

1222
01:04:11,077 --> 01:04:13,312
Mr. Wildhorn didn't
really shoot your clown.

1223
01:04:13,380 --> 01:04:16,949
He just, well, wanted
to get his attention.

1224
01:04:17,016 --> 01:04:18,934
Can you read me
the elephant story?

1225
01:04:19,002 --> 01:04:22,020
I don't see why not.
You ready?

1226
01:04:22,088 --> 01:04:23,121
Ready.

1227
01:04:23,189 --> 01:04:24,273
Okay.

1228
01:04:25,341 --> 01:04:26,975
"Once upon a time,

1229
01:04:27,042 --> 01:04:31,813
"inside a finely-tuned
piano in an old house

1230
01:04:31,881 --> 01:04:34,583
"there lived
a family of mice.

1231
01:04:34,651 --> 01:04:38,453
"They had everything
mice could possibly
want in the world

1232
01:04:38,521 --> 01:04:42,023
"because this mouse family
had wisely invested

1233
01:04:42,091 --> 01:04:45,427
in The Cheesecake Factory."

1234
01:04:45,495 --> 01:04:46,878
[giggling]

1235
01:04:46,946 --> 01:04:48,897
"Mrs. Mouse
made sure their home

1236
01:04:48,965 --> 01:04:51,683
"was always filled
with music

1237
01:04:51,751 --> 01:04:55,387
"by jumping up and down
on the keyboard.

1238
01:04:55,455 --> 01:04:58,189
"The only problem
they had

1239
01:04:58,258 --> 01:05:02,827
was the cat that
lived in the house
with them."

1240
01:05:02,895 --> 01:05:05,597
Is the cat gonna
eat the mouses?

1241
01:05:05,665 --> 01:05:07,899
Oh, well, let's hope
Mr. Wildhorn

1242
01:05:07,967 --> 01:05:10,102
isn't taking the story
in that direction.

1243
01:05:10,169 --> 01:05:10,969
[sneezing]

1244
01:05:11,037 --> 01:05:12,637
Oh, well, bless you,
sweetheart.

1245
01:05:12,705 --> 01:05:14,072
Thank you.

1246
01:05:14,140 --> 01:05:17,943
"One day, on the brightest
of summer mornings,

1247
01:05:18,010 --> 01:05:21,479
the littlest mouse heard
a knock at the front door."

1248
01:05:21,781 --> 01:05:23,398
Who's there?

1249
01:05:23,466 --> 01:05:24,933
"She opened the door,

1250
01:05:25,000 --> 01:05:27,352
"and there standing
before her

1251
01:05:27,420 --> 01:05:29,321
"was the grandest elephant

1252
01:05:29,389 --> 01:05:31,790
"ever seen
by a little mouse,

1253
01:05:31,857 --> 01:05:33,858
"or any mouse
for that matter.

1254
01:05:33,926 --> 01:05:37,896
"'I'm pleased to meet you.
My name is Tony.

1255
01:05:37,964 --> 01:05:39,398
"'I heard
the beautiful music

1256
01:05:39,465 --> 01:05:42,367
and wanted to see where
it was coming from.'"

1257
01:05:50,276 --> 01:05:53,645
[voice of Monte] "Tony,
a traveling magician by day

1258
01:05:53,713 --> 01:05:55,914
"and an opera singer by night,

1259
01:05:55,982 --> 01:05:57,349
"cast a magic spell

1260
01:05:57,417 --> 01:06:00,352
"so the mice would be
invisible to the cat.

1261
01:06:00,420 --> 01:06:03,589
"This made the mouse
family feel very safe

1262
01:06:03,656 --> 01:06:06,425
"and everyone was very happy.

1263
01:06:06,493 --> 01:06:07,759
"Mrs. Mouse was so happy

1264
01:06:07,827 --> 01:06:10,929
"that when it was time
for Tony to leave,

1265
01:06:10,997 --> 01:06:13,932
"she scampered
all the way up his trunk

1266
01:06:14,000 --> 01:06:16,768
"and gave him
a kiss on the cheek.

1267
01:06:16,836 --> 01:06:19,971
Tony promptly fainted."

1268
01:06:22,342 --> 01:06:25,244
I think
this elephant likes me.

1269
01:06:38,925 --> 01:06:40,325
Well, I suppose

1270
01:06:40,392 --> 01:06:42,377
I could smear the ball
with peanut butter,

1271
01:06:42,445 --> 01:06:46,147
but that would be
beneath your dignity...

1272
01:06:46,215 --> 01:06:47,282
and mine.

1273
01:06:59,111 --> 01:07:02,747
Well, this isn't
your first raft, Mrs. O'Neil.

1274
01:07:02,815 --> 01:07:04,483
Finn did most of the work,

1275
01:07:04,550 --> 01:07:07,585
with a little help
from Diego Santana.

1276
01:07:07,653 --> 01:07:08,853
Ah.

1277
01:07:10,990 --> 01:07:12,391
Where is everybody?

1278
01:07:12,458 --> 01:07:15,510
Karen took them into town
for some ice cream.

1279
01:07:15,578 --> 01:07:17,395
You didn't get to go?

1280
01:07:17,463 --> 01:07:19,581
It was a plot.

1281
01:07:19,648 --> 01:07:21,950
So I could
finish the raft.

1282
01:07:23,519 --> 01:07:26,321
She's had her heart set
on sailing to the island
this summer...

1283
01:07:26,388 --> 01:07:29,107
and school starts
in three weeks.

1284
01:07:31,310 --> 01:07:32,343
I see.

1285
01:07:33,979 --> 01:07:35,214
Flora greatly appreciated

1286
01:07:35,281 --> 01:07:37,799
The Elephant
Who Stays Forever.

1287
01:07:37,867 --> 01:07:40,369
I was hoping she'd like it.

1288
01:07:40,503 --> 01:07:44,256
She made me read it to her
several times,

1289
01:07:44,323 --> 01:07:47,192
and she asked me

1290
01:07:47,260 --> 01:07:49,527
if you would
write more Tony stories.

1291
01:07:51,914 --> 01:07:56,584
Well... I wouldn't
want to disappoint her.

1292
01:08:00,739 --> 01:08:05,043
[piano playing]

1293
01:08:07,580 --> 01:08:11,549
[telephone ringing]

1294
01:08:11,618 --> 01:08:13,384
[recording] Hi, it's Dave.

1295
01:08:13,452 --> 01:08:15,621
That's me on drums.
Leave a message.

1296
01:08:15,688 --> 01:08:16,822
[beep]

1297
01:08:16,889 --> 01:08:18,223
Monte, it's Joe again.

1298
01:08:18,290 --> 01:08:20,558
It's really important
you call me back.

1299
01:08:23,963 --> 01:08:26,064
Important for who?

1300
01:08:36,658 --> 01:08:37,592
Willow...

1301
01:08:37,659 --> 01:08:39,311
No, thanks.

1302
01:08:39,378 --> 01:08:40,646
Come on, Willow.
This is gonna be

1303
01:08:40,713 --> 01:08:42,864
the adventure
of a lifetime.

1304
01:08:42,931 --> 01:08:43,698
Of a lifetime.

1305
01:08:44,016 --> 01:08:45,550
Finnegan is not going
to that island

1306
01:08:45,618 --> 01:08:47,319
without her big sister.

1307
01:08:48,303 --> 01:08:49,321
Fine.

1308
01:08:50,990 --> 01:08:57,328
[music]

1309
01:09:28,327 --> 01:09:29,511
A swing.

1310
01:09:29,579 --> 01:09:31,813
Will you push me, Willow?

1311
01:09:31,880 --> 01:09:33,648
Sure, Carl. Hop on.

1312
01:09:37,537 --> 01:09:39,087
Whee-hee!

1313
01:09:40,673 --> 01:09:41,640
Whoo!

1314
01:09:41,874 --> 01:09:43,658
Higher. Whee-hee.

1315
01:09:44,726 --> 01:09:46,328
Hang on!

1316
01:09:46,395 --> 01:09:47,546
Push harder.

1317
01:09:47,613 --> 01:09:49,564
Fun?
Yeah!

1318
01:09:49,632 --> 01:09:51,633
Oh!

1319
01:09:54,904 --> 01:09:56,104
I think I'm drowning!

1320
01:09:56,171 --> 01:09:59,908
Carl! Carl, it's shallow.
Just stand up.

1321
01:09:59,976 --> 01:10:01,326
Help me!

1322
01:10:01,977 --> 01:10:03,961
Carl, it's shallow.

1323
01:10:05,030 --> 01:10:06,531
You're not drowning.

1324
01:10:10,903 --> 01:10:12,670
That was close.

1325
01:10:39,615 --> 01:10:40,665
Whoa.

1326
01:10:42,885 --> 01:10:44,352
FLORA:
What is it, Finn?

1327
01:10:44,419 --> 01:10:47,488
It's a lunchbox.
I found it on the island.

1328
01:10:47,556 --> 01:10:48,723
What's inside?

1329
01:10:48,791 --> 01:10:49,758
I haven't
opened it yet.

1330
01:10:49,825 --> 01:10:51,309
Why not?

1331
01:10:51,377 --> 01:10:53,144
Because there might not
be anything good in it.

1332
01:10:53,212 --> 01:10:55,146
This way, I can think
there's something good
even if there's not.

1333
01:10:55,214 --> 01:10:57,048
Do you know how stupid
that sounds?

1334
01:10:57,116 --> 01:10:58,799
No. It's
like what Monte says,

1335
01:10:58,868 --> 01:11:00,134
seeing
what's not there.

1336
01:11:00,402 --> 01:11:02,754
I'll open it.
I wanna see
what is there.

1337
01:11:02,988 --> 01:11:04,422
Maybe it's money.

1338
01:11:04,490 --> 01:11:07,692
Might be a chopped
off hand, Willow Tree.

1339
01:11:07,759 --> 01:11:08,543
Don't open it!

1340
01:11:12,398 --> 01:11:14,015
Wow...
Look at all this stuff.

1341
01:11:14,083 --> 01:11:15,550
Look, it's a diary.

1342
01:11:15,685 --> 01:11:18,035
"Property
of Charlotte Reilly,
Seventh Grade."

1343
01:11:18,103 --> 01:11:19,771
Who's that?

1344
01:11:19,839 --> 01:11:21,339
That's Mama!

1345
01:11:21,406 --> 01:11:22,941
Probably everything
we wanna know about her

1346
01:11:23,008 --> 01:11:24,909
when she was
a kid is in here.

1347
01:11:24,977 --> 01:11:26,578
What do we wanna
know about her?

1348
01:11:26,646 --> 01:11:28,279
We should probably
give it back to her.

1349
01:11:28,347 --> 01:11:29,881
I think she'd
want it back.

1350
01:11:30,149 --> 01:11:32,734
We should make
her a sandwich.

1351
01:12:07,019 --> 01:12:08,319
Lovely day, Mr. Wildhorn.

1352
01:12:08,521 --> 01:12:10,021
Yes, ma'am.
It's shaping up to be

1353
01:12:10,089 --> 01:12:13,357
a considerably lovely day.

1354
01:12:17,079 --> 01:12:18,780
More Tony?

1355
01:12:18,847 --> 01:12:20,264
Yes, ma'am.

1356
01:12:20,500 --> 01:12:21,832
I'm sure Flora
will be delighted,

1357
01:12:21,900 --> 01:12:24,435
and I will read this to her
tonight at bedtime.

1358
01:12:24,503 --> 01:12:25,603
Good.

1359
01:12:28,123 --> 01:12:29,307
Thank you.

1360
01:12:32,194 --> 01:12:34,679
Spot, that lady has a way

1361
01:12:34,747 --> 01:12:37,582
of making me
sit taller in the saddle.

1362
01:12:40,136 --> 01:12:43,187
Flora, look what
Mr. Wildhorn gave me.

1363
01:12:43,255 --> 01:12:45,156
Tony the Elephant?

1364
01:12:45,224 --> 01:12:46,290
Who's Tony
the Elephant?

1365
01:12:46,609 --> 01:12:48,109
Mr. Wildhorn wrote a story

1366
01:12:48,177 --> 01:12:49,277
for Flora's birthday.

1367
01:12:49,344 --> 01:12:51,112
He did what?

1368
01:12:51,180 --> 01:12:53,381
Read Tony, Mommy.

1369
01:12:53,515 --> 01:12:56,484
Let me see that!
No, no. We'll
read it tonight.

1370
01:12:56,551 --> 01:12:59,020
Today, I want
all of you girls
to go outside

1371
01:12:59,087 --> 01:13:00,872
and play
in the fresh air.

1372
01:13:00,940 --> 01:13:03,457
Come on.
We can ride into town.

1373
01:13:05,077 --> 01:13:07,228
Monte! Monte!

1374
01:13:07,296 --> 01:13:10,782
Monte! I'm calling you out!

1375
01:13:12,418 --> 01:13:14,502
You gave up Jubal McLaws
for an elephant?

1376
01:13:14,570 --> 01:13:16,320
You told me
Jubal saved your life!

1377
01:13:16,388 --> 01:13:17,255
Then you shoot him
in the back!

1378
01:13:17,323 --> 01:13:19,573
Oh, now, hold on.

1379
01:13:19,641 --> 01:13:21,842
I don't call writing
about an elephant

1380
01:13:21,910 --> 01:13:23,177
shooting Jubal
in the back.

1381
01:13:23,245 --> 01:13:25,764
Jubal hasn't come
calling in years.

1382
01:13:25,831 --> 01:13:28,032
I ca-- I can't
write what's not there.

1383
01:13:28,100 --> 01:13:29,968
You tell me to see
what's not there.

1384
01:13:30,035 --> 01:13:32,403
Why can't you write
what's not there?

1385
01:13:34,556 --> 01:13:36,841
You're a no-good drunk
and a liar!

1386
01:13:36,909 --> 01:13:38,376
Finnegan!

1387
01:13:38,661 --> 01:13:40,562
He's a damn
bamboozler, Willow!

1388
01:13:47,870 --> 01:13:49,371
Mr. Wildhorn?

1389
01:13:49,438 --> 01:13:52,289
My sister believes
you're something special.

1390
01:13:52,625 --> 01:13:54,108
Are you something special?

1391
01:13:54,176 --> 01:13:58,245
Can't say that I ever
thought of myself
like that.

1392
01:13:58,313 --> 01:14:00,298
Well, you'd better be.

1393
01:14:00,366 --> 01:14:02,033
'Cause otherwise,
you don't deserve Finnegan.

1394
01:14:03,636 --> 01:14:04,936
I really hope you two make up,

1395
01:14:05,004 --> 01:14:08,372
because I'd hate to see you
lose a friend like her.

1396
01:14:20,786 --> 01:14:24,522
[voice of Monte]
"Sometimes, talking to people
wasn't easy for Tony.

1397
01:14:24,590 --> 01:14:27,825
"So he kept writing letters
to Mrs. Mouse,

1398
01:14:27,893 --> 01:14:30,762
"faithfully delivered
by the tree toad.

1399
01:14:30,829 --> 01:14:35,633
"Then a really amazing elephant
thing happened.

1400
01:14:35,701 --> 01:14:38,869
"When elephants find
they're too nervous to speak,

1401
01:14:38,937 --> 01:14:41,172
"they begin to dance.

1402
01:14:41,239 --> 01:14:43,341
"Tony loved to waltz.

1403
01:14:43,409 --> 01:14:46,177
"And before he even realized it,

1404
01:14:46,244 --> 01:14:49,947
"he found himself waltzing
with Mrs. Mouse

1405
01:14:50,015 --> 01:14:52,483
under the warm moonlight."

1406
01:15:03,128 --> 01:15:05,146
[knocking on door]

1407
01:15:05,213 --> 01:15:06,514
It's open!

1408
01:15:16,057 --> 01:15:18,159
Hello, Joe.
Been expecting you.

1409
01:15:18,226 --> 01:15:21,596
You might want to
return a phone call
every once in a while,

1410
01:15:21,664 --> 01:15:23,898
especially to someone
you've known so long.

1411
01:15:25,584 --> 01:15:27,252
How's the book business, Joe?

1412
01:15:27,319 --> 01:15:31,339
Nobody reads unless
they can download.

1413
01:15:31,406 --> 01:15:34,208
Why wouldn't you
want to hold a book?

1414
01:15:34,276 --> 01:15:36,377
You've got a dog!

1415
01:15:36,445 --> 01:15:39,897
Yeah, I'm dog-sitting
for the summer.

1416
01:15:39,965 --> 01:15:40,848
You seem different.

1417
01:15:42,868 --> 01:15:46,337
You're not, uh...
yourself.

1418
01:15:46,105 --> 01:15:47,421
Sober, you mean?

1419
01:15:49,124 --> 01:15:50,691
Well, I've stopped before.

1420
01:15:50,759 --> 01:15:52,927
And I'll probably
start up again.

1421
01:15:52,995 --> 01:15:55,363
But right now,
I'm seeing things
with a clear eye.

1422
01:15:55,431 --> 01:15:57,732
And quite frankly,
I like the view.

1423
01:15:57,799 --> 01:15:59,234
What can I do
for you, Joe?

1424
01:15:59,301 --> 01:16:02,020
I've come here today
to change your life.

1425
01:16:03,589 --> 01:16:05,857
You'll collect your usual
commission for that?

1426
01:16:05,924 --> 01:16:07,258
I certainly do.

1427
01:16:07,325 --> 01:16:08,943
I brought
Luke Ford with me.

1428
01:16:09,011 --> 01:16:10,144
He's waiting outside.

1429
01:16:10,212 --> 01:16:11,545
The Luke Ford?

1430
01:16:11,613 --> 01:16:13,497
The Luke Ford.

1431
01:16:13,565 --> 01:16:14,933
You mind
if I invite him in?

1432
01:16:15,000 --> 01:16:15,900
Be impolite not to.

1433
01:16:15,968 --> 01:16:18,652
That's what I was
thinking. Luke?

1434
01:16:18,720 --> 01:16:20,572
Luke, why don't
you join us?

1435
01:16:22,675 --> 01:16:25,009
Come meet the great
Monte Wildhorn.

1436
01:16:27,513 --> 01:16:29,113
Sorry, for just
showing up like this,

1437
01:16:29,180 --> 01:16:31,348
but Joe said it was the only way
I might get to meet you.

1438
01:16:31,417 --> 01:16:32,483
I'm Luke Ford.

1439
01:16:32,551 --> 01:16:34,819
You certainly are.

1440
01:16:34,887 --> 01:16:37,521
I'm really pleased
to make your acquaintance.

1441
01:16:39,541 --> 01:16:40,558
Have a seat.

1442
01:16:44,646 --> 01:16:46,747
Luke is the reason
that I've been trying

1443
01:16:46,815 --> 01:16:49,250
to get a hold of you
all summer.

1444
01:16:49,318 --> 01:16:53,254
I know you wanted your space,
but he's been rather insistent

1445
01:16:53,322 --> 01:16:55,957
on acquiring the rights
to Jubal McLaws.

1446
01:16:56,024 --> 01:16:58,109
Is that right?

1447
01:16:58,177 --> 01:16:59,460
How about that, huh?

1448
01:16:59,527 --> 01:17:01,679
Well, Jubal's
not for sale.

1449
01:17:01,747 --> 01:17:05,033
Oh, come on now.
Hear him out.

1450
01:17:05,100 --> 01:17:07,535
He is just trying to make you
a rich son of a bitch.

1451
01:17:07,602 --> 01:17:09,337
I'm already
a son of a bitch.

1452
01:17:09,404 --> 01:17:13,607
And I don't care to
be rich, but thanks
for thinking of me.

1453
01:17:13,675 --> 01:17:15,209
This could be
a real fresh start for you.

1454
01:17:15,277 --> 01:17:17,478
Granted, you'll have to take a
sabbatical from the dog-sitting.

1455
01:17:17,546 --> 01:17:18,897
I like dog-sitting.

1456
01:17:18,964 --> 01:17:21,348
Monte, I'm a huge fan
of the old Westerns,

1457
01:17:21,416 --> 01:17:24,351
and I'm convinced that
there's still some life
left in the genre.

1458
01:17:24,620 --> 01:17:28,255
The Saga of Jubal McLaws

1459
01:17:28,323 --> 01:17:30,024
is the best Western novel
I ever read.

1460
01:17:30,091 --> 01:17:31,759
If you allow me,

1461
01:17:31,826 --> 01:17:33,744
I'd be honored to be the one
to bring Jubal to life.

1462
01:17:33,979 --> 01:17:36,014
All due respect, Mr. Ford,

1463
01:17:36,081 --> 01:17:40,051
but my late wife has already
pulled off that miracle.

1464
01:17:40,185 --> 01:17:43,237
Then consider your readership--
this movie gets produced,

1465
01:17:43,305 --> 01:17:45,607
they'll increase
a thousand fold.

1466
01:17:45,674 --> 01:17:47,441
Isn't that what
you always wanted?

1467
01:17:47,509 --> 01:17:48,792
I thought it was.

1468
01:17:50,763 --> 01:17:53,197
Mr. Ford, I appreciate
your taking the time

1469
01:17:53,265 --> 01:17:55,700
to come out here,
I really do.

1470
01:17:55,768 --> 01:17:59,103
If ever there was a man
to play Jubal, you'd be him.

1471
01:18:00,522 --> 01:18:02,790
But right now,
I'm in a pretty good...

1472
01:18:06,161 --> 01:18:10,865
Most times, real life
doesn't measure up
to what's in our heads,

1473
01:18:10,933 --> 01:18:14,335
but every now and then,
it comes pretty close.

1474
01:18:14,403 --> 01:18:18,923
You happened
to catch me in one
of those rarefied moments.

1475
01:18:18,991 --> 01:18:21,492
So if it's
all the same to you,

1476
01:18:21,560 --> 01:18:24,178
I'll stick with real life
for a spell.

1477
01:18:26,031 --> 01:18:28,182
You're making a big mistake,
and I gotta tell you,

1478
01:18:28,249 --> 01:18:29,550
this could be your last chance.

1479
01:18:29,785 --> 01:18:31,835
I don't believe
in last chances, Joe.

1480
01:18:31,904 --> 01:18:33,137
I've had too many of them.

1481
01:18:33,205 --> 01:18:34,822
Monte!
Joe...

1482
01:18:34,889 --> 01:18:36,040
meeting's over.

1483
01:18:41,914 --> 01:18:43,347
It's real nice
meeting you.

1484
01:18:43,415 --> 01:18:48,186
[piano playing]

1485
01:18:48,253 --> 01:18:49,320
That's pretty.

1486
01:18:49,387 --> 01:18:51,138
It's Mrs. O'Neil,

1487
01:18:51,206 --> 01:18:52,490
next door.

1488
01:18:52,558 --> 01:18:54,325
Real fine lady.

1489
01:18:55,810 --> 01:18:59,130
Right now,
she's talking to me.

1490
01:18:59,197 --> 01:19:00,264
And if you don't mind,

1491
01:19:00,332 --> 01:19:01,999
it's a personal
conversation.

1492
01:19:04,286 --> 01:19:05,719
Mr. Wildhorn,

1493
01:19:05,988 --> 01:19:08,672
it's a pleasure
not doing business with you.

1494
01:19:15,814 --> 01:19:18,199
How much longer
are you here?

1495
01:19:18,266 --> 01:19:19,434
Couple of weeks.

1496
01:19:19,501 --> 01:19:22,403
Fixed all right for cash?

1497
01:19:22,470 --> 01:19:24,255
Same as always.

1498
01:19:24,323 --> 01:19:25,006
That's what I thought.

1499
01:19:25,074 --> 01:19:26,891
No, thanks, Joe.

1500
01:19:30,296 --> 01:19:32,062
You take care.

1501
01:19:42,757 --> 01:19:46,894
[playing Beethoven's
Pathetique Sonata]

1502
01:20:11,319 --> 01:20:14,689
CHARLOTTE:
I believe you owe me
a toast, Mr. Wildhorn.

1503
01:20:14,756 --> 01:20:19,243
Here's to you,
Mrs. O'Neil, and a face

1504
01:20:19,311 --> 01:20:22,947
that gives the moonlight
something worth shining on.

1505
01:20:30,155 --> 01:20:32,823
What do you want
out of life, Mr. Wildhorn?

1506
01:20:33,975 --> 01:20:36,444
I'd settle for
more nights like this.

1507
01:20:38,714 --> 01:20:41,281
I told my girls
that one of the great pleasures

1508
01:20:41,349 --> 01:20:44,284
life has to offer is their
own search after the heart.

1509
01:20:46,071 --> 01:20:47,205
Yes, ma'am.

1510
01:20:48,824 --> 01:20:52,125
What would the woman who
captures your heart be like?

1511
01:20:52,193 --> 01:20:55,329
She'd have your way
of walking into a room.

1512
01:20:58,550 --> 01:20:59,883
How do I do that?

1513
01:21:02,904 --> 01:21:06,707
It's sunny outside.
There's a light rainfall.

1514
01:21:08,376 --> 01:21:12,079
You know how it feels
when a warm breeze
comes with the rain?

1515
01:21:15,183 --> 01:21:18,052
That's how you walk
into a room.

1516
01:21:22,006 --> 01:21:23,724
That's some kind of walking
I'd have to do

1517
01:21:23,792 --> 01:21:26,059
to be worthy
of such lovely words.

1518
01:21:26,127 --> 01:21:28,629
And I'd like her
to have your ears.

1519
01:21:28,697 --> 01:21:30,631
[laughing]

1520
01:21:30,699 --> 01:21:32,299
My ears?

1521
01:21:32,367 --> 01:21:35,837
If you don't mind me
saying so, Mrs. O'Neil,

1522
01:21:35,904 --> 01:21:39,841
your ears look like they
can handle the soft whisper.

1523
01:21:39,908 --> 01:21:44,562
And if you don't mind
my inquiring, Mr. Wildhorn,

1524
01:21:44,629 --> 01:21:46,863
what would the whisper be?

1525
01:21:47,099 --> 01:21:49,634
Well, it would be
different every night.

1526
01:21:53,004 --> 01:21:55,273
Maybe you could whisper
it in my ear while we dance.

1527
01:21:56,925 --> 01:21:59,826
I have it on good authority
that you love to waltz.

1528
01:22:01,429 --> 01:22:02,730
And so I do.

1529
01:22:38,984 --> 01:22:41,002
[knocking on door]

1530
01:22:42,854 --> 01:22:44,155
CHARLOTTE:
Mr. Wildhorn?

1531
01:22:44,222 --> 01:22:45,289
[porch door opens]

1532
01:22:45,357 --> 01:22:46,657
Uh, I'll be right there!

1533
01:22:46,992 --> 01:22:49,426
Just a minute.
Just a minute.

1534
01:22:49,495 --> 01:22:50,728
I'll be right there.

1535
01:22:50,796 --> 01:22:53,397
If it's too early,
I can come back.

1536
01:22:53,465 --> 01:22:54,599
Oh, no, no, no.

1537
01:22:54,666 --> 01:22:57,117
Not at all. Not at all.

1538
01:22:59,287 --> 01:23:03,757
Ah, Mrs. O'Neil.
What a pleasant surprise.

1539
01:23:03,825 --> 01:23:04,992
What can I do for you?

1540
01:23:05,059 --> 01:23:06,861
I have something
of a favor to ask you

1541
01:23:06,928 --> 01:23:08,646
if it wouldn't be too
much of an imposition.

1542
01:23:08,714 --> 01:23:12,499
After the way you played
the piano last night,
no favor is too big.

1543
01:23:12,567 --> 01:23:13,984
Thank you.

1544
01:23:14,052 --> 01:23:15,286
It's just that
I have to go into the city

1545
01:23:15,353 --> 01:23:17,337
for the day
to meet with the lawyers.

1546
01:23:17,405 --> 01:23:19,991
Jack and I have
a few final things
to work out.

1547
01:23:20,058 --> 01:23:22,810
I was wondering
if you might

1548
01:23:22,877 --> 01:23:24,678
stay with the girls
until I get back.

1549
01:23:24,947 --> 01:23:27,031
It shouldn't be too late.

1550
01:23:29,952 --> 01:23:31,635
You want me to baby-sit?

1551
01:23:31,703 --> 01:23:34,004
If you wouldn't mind.

1552
01:23:37,692 --> 01:23:39,559
No, no.

1553
01:23:39,628 --> 01:23:41,294
No, I accept the challenge.

1554
01:23:41,362 --> 01:23:44,815
Wonderful. Thank you,
Mr. Wildhorn.

1555
01:23:48,136 --> 01:23:51,104
There's a casserole
in the fridge for dinner.

1556
01:23:51,172 --> 01:23:54,592
And if you need to reach me,
the girls have my cell number.

1557
01:23:54,660 --> 01:23:56,777
Okay, now, I should be home
before you go to bed,

1558
01:23:56,844 --> 01:23:59,813
but Mr. Wildhorn
agreed to stay with you.

1559
01:23:59,881 --> 01:24:01,949
It's okay, Mom.
I can take care
of everything.

1560
01:24:02,016 --> 01:24:04,068
Yeah, Mom.
We don't need any help.

1561
01:24:04,135 --> 01:24:05,086
Willow can watch us.

1562
01:24:05,153 --> 01:24:06,620
I know, this is just in case.

1563
01:24:06,905 --> 01:24:11,892
And I expect you to behave
like ladies while I'm gone.

1564
01:24:11,960 --> 01:24:13,694
Oh, good luck.

1565
01:24:13,762 --> 01:24:14,778
Oh, don't worry about us.

1566
01:24:14,846 --> 01:24:16,146
You go
and fight your battles.

1567
01:24:16,214 --> 01:24:17,481
We'll protect
the homestead.

1568
01:24:19,600 --> 01:24:21,068
Okay...

1569
01:24:34,266 --> 01:24:36,216
Who's up for
some high-stakes poker?

1570
01:24:36,284 --> 01:24:39,419
Five-card draw. Deuces
and one-eyed jacks wild?

1571
01:24:48,697 --> 01:24:49,830
I'll play.

1572
01:24:49,897 --> 01:24:51,715
How much you got?

1573
01:24:51,983 --> 01:24:54,218
Mom! Mom, wait!

1574
01:25:01,559 --> 01:25:02,793
Is Dad gonna be there?

1575
01:25:02,861 --> 01:25:05,996
Or is it
just the lawyers?

1576
01:25:06,064 --> 01:25:08,332
Dad will be there.

1577
01:25:10,902 --> 01:25:12,303
Will you say
hello for me?

1578
01:25:12,370 --> 01:25:14,355
Of course.

1579
01:25:18,893 --> 01:25:20,060
I love you, Mom.

1580
01:25:23,682 --> 01:25:24,982
I love you, too.

1581
01:25:41,749 --> 01:25:44,517
Come on, Flora!
Jump.

1582
01:25:48,239 --> 01:25:50,173
Whoo!

1583
01:26:06,491 --> 01:26:08,776
That's quite an arm
you got there.

1584
01:26:13,581 --> 01:26:15,466
You ever play any ball?

1585
01:26:23,709 --> 01:26:25,776
When I was 17 years old,

1586
01:26:25,843 --> 01:26:28,879
I could throw a baseball
90 miles an hour.

1587
01:26:28,947 --> 01:26:31,548
Had a real live arm.

1588
01:26:33,218 --> 01:26:34,835
Got me
a minor league contract

1589
01:26:34,903 --> 01:26:38,105
for the St. Louis Cardinals.

1590
01:26:38,173 --> 01:26:40,640
I played eight years
with the Memphis Chickasaws

1591
01:26:40,708 --> 01:26:42,943
and the Portland Beavers.

1592
01:26:43,011 --> 01:26:46,113
Double A, Triple A.

1593
01:26:46,181 --> 01:26:50,301
Even worked my way up
to the bigs at the end
of a couple of seasons.

1594
01:26:52,337 --> 01:26:56,206
One summer day,
we were playing a doubleheader.

1595
01:26:58,009 --> 01:26:59,510
I was pitching the opener.

1596
01:27:01,312 --> 01:27:05,015
First batter steps into the box.

1597
01:27:05,083 --> 01:27:07,817
I leaned in to get the sign,

1598
01:27:07,885 --> 01:27:09,719
and out of the corner of my eye,

1599
01:27:09,787 --> 01:27:14,691
I saw the most beautiful girl
I'd ever seen in my life.

1600
01:27:16,410 --> 01:27:20,464
She takes a seat right
behind the catcher,

1601
01:27:20,532 --> 01:27:23,967
and I can't
take my eyes off her.

1602
01:27:24,035 --> 01:27:26,937
I was knocked out
in the first inning.

1603
01:27:27,005 --> 01:27:30,791
But it was
worth it.

1604
01:27:30,859 --> 01:27:33,110
Her name was Mary,

1605
01:27:33,177 --> 01:27:36,213
and we were married
eight months later.

1606
01:27:36,415 --> 01:27:40,217
She wanted to have
a lot of kids.

1607
01:27:40,284 --> 01:27:44,622
I was all right
with that.

1608
01:27:44,689 --> 01:27:47,173
Two days before
my 25th birthday,

1609
01:27:47,241 --> 01:27:49,710
I got a call from the Cardinals.

1610
01:27:49,777 --> 01:27:51,077
They needed a new starter.

1611
01:27:53,548 --> 01:27:56,016
I was on my way home
from the ballpark

1612
01:27:56,083 --> 01:27:57,518
to tell Mary the good news...

1613
01:27:58,686 --> 01:28:00,754
when a drunk driver
ran a red light...

1614
01:28:03,324 --> 01:28:05,325
I ended up in this chair.

1615
01:28:09,630 --> 01:28:13,066
I was sure Mary would leave me.

1616
01:28:13,134 --> 01:28:15,569
There were times
when I almost wished she would.

1617
01:28:18,139 --> 01:28:20,440
But she never gave up on me.

1618
01:28:22,343 --> 01:28:24,110
She used to tell me,

1619
01:28:24,178 --> 01:28:26,747
one door closes,
another one opens.

1620
01:28:28,332 --> 01:28:31,234
I didn't buy into it
until one day I looked up

1621
01:28:31,302 --> 01:28:33,870
and there was Jubal McLaws,

1622
01:28:33,938 --> 01:28:38,742
a half smile on his face,
staring right back at me.

1623
01:28:42,364 --> 01:28:45,799
Jubal and Mary
gave me my life back.

1624
01:28:50,538 --> 01:28:52,573
Six years ago, Mary died...

1625
01:28:55,377 --> 01:28:56,810
and Jubal went with her.

1626
01:28:58,846 --> 01:29:01,014
All doors closed,

1627
01:29:01,082 --> 01:29:02,383
bolted shut.

1628
01:29:04,753 --> 01:29:07,688
Until one day,

1629
01:29:07,756 --> 01:29:10,557
a nine year-old girl
named Finnegan O'Neil

1630
01:29:10,625 --> 01:29:16,330
showed up at my door
and gave me back my legs.

1631
01:29:23,171 --> 01:29:24,604
How did I do that?

1632
01:29:27,075 --> 01:29:29,843
By believing with me.

1633
01:29:29,911 --> 01:29:32,880
That's how I was able
to dance in the moonlight.

1634
01:29:35,817 --> 01:29:36,917
You danced?

1635
01:29:36,985 --> 01:29:40,303
In my mind, I sure did.

1636
01:29:47,312 --> 01:29:48,645
Can't they fix you?

1637
01:29:49,881 --> 01:29:51,531
No, Finn, they can't.

1638
01:29:56,921 --> 01:29:58,855
Maybe you'll get a miracle.

1639
01:30:00,725 --> 01:30:05,562
The way I see it,
I already got my miracle.

1640
01:30:12,604 --> 01:30:14,371
Okay, so first you
go to "contacts."

1641
01:30:14,438 --> 01:30:15,705
What's "contacts"?

1642
01:30:15,774 --> 01:30:17,707
It's the thing
that looks like a book.

1643
01:30:17,776 --> 01:30:19,276
I see a clock.

1644
01:30:19,343 --> 01:30:20,360
It's next to
the clock, see?

1645
01:30:20,428 --> 01:30:22,262
All right.
How do I get there?

1646
01:30:22,329 --> 01:30:23,063
See the little ball
in the middle?

1647
01:30:23,130 --> 01:30:24,148
Yeah.

1648
01:30:24,215 --> 01:30:26,166
Roll it.
Roll it.

1649
01:30:26,234 --> 01:30:27,234
With your thumb.

1650
01:30:27,302 --> 01:30:29,603
With my thumb, okay.

1651
01:30:29,670 --> 01:30:32,139
Oh! There it is.
Now what?

1652
01:30:32,206 --> 01:30:33,974
[together] Press it.

1653
01:30:35,994 --> 01:30:37,795
Now it's showing me the time.

1654
01:30:37,862 --> 01:30:39,045
That's because you rolled it
while pressing it.

1655
01:30:39,113 --> 01:30:40,330
Go back one.

1656
01:30:40,398 --> 01:30:42,532
Ah, I don't believe I will.

1657
01:30:42,601 --> 01:30:45,636
Like I stated at the outset,
it's not for me.

1658
01:30:45,704 --> 01:30:49,056
Now, who can I interest
in a Mr. Pibb?

1659
01:30:49,124 --> 01:30:50,507
[together] Me.

1660
01:30:50,575 --> 01:30:51,909
Come on.

1661
01:30:55,780 --> 01:31:00,467
Uh... you let me know
if I'm doing something wrong.

1662
01:31:00,535 --> 01:31:04,004
I never put kids
to bed before.

1663
01:31:04,072 --> 01:31:05,271
We'll help you, Monte.

1664
01:31:05,339 --> 01:31:07,407
Oh...

1665
01:31:07,475 --> 01:31:09,776
Shouldn't Mama be home now?

1666
01:31:09,843 --> 01:31:10,828
She just texted me.

1667
01:31:10,895 --> 01:31:12,646
She'll be home
in a couple of hours.

1668
01:31:17,818 --> 01:31:18,952
Well, now.

1669
01:31:24,108 --> 01:31:25,942
All right, then...

1670
01:31:28,913 --> 01:31:29,946
get some shuteye.

1671
01:31:47,865 --> 01:31:50,100
We're in Dog Dave's bed.

1672
01:31:50,168 --> 01:31:52,702
[giggling]

1673
01:32:01,446 --> 01:32:03,880
I couldn't agree more.

1674
01:32:03,948 --> 01:32:06,967
A night like this
certainly puts you in the mood.

1675
01:32:08,536 --> 01:32:10,503
Good evening,
Mr. Wildhorn.

1676
01:32:10,571 --> 01:32:12,188
I'm sorry
I'm so late.

1677
01:32:12,256 --> 01:32:13,590
Oh, that's all right.

1678
01:32:15,059 --> 01:32:16,393
I didn't know what to do,

1679
01:32:16,461 --> 01:32:18,695
so I put the little ones
in Dog Dave's bed.

1680
01:32:18,763 --> 01:32:20,196
[laughing]

1681
01:32:20,365 --> 01:32:23,033
That'll be
all they remember
about this summer.

1682
01:32:24,735 --> 01:32:26,403
Willow fell
asleep on the couch.

1683
01:32:26,470 --> 01:32:27,571
I hope they weren't
too much trouble.

1684
01:32:27,638 --> 01:32:29,639
Oh, just the opposite.

1685
01:32:32,893 --> 01:32:35,862
Well, I guess I better
take 'em off your hands.

1686
01:32:35,930 --> 01:32:37,331
I don't mind

1687
01:32:37,398 --> 01:32:39,666
if you wanna
leave 'em for the night.

1688
01:32:39,733 --> 01:32:40,950
Are you sure?

1689
01:32:41,018 --> 01:32:43,203
It'd be a shame
to wake 'em at this hour.

1690
01:32:43,471 --> 01:32:46,690
Oh. Okay. Thanks.

1691
01:32:50,512 --> 01:32:52,345
Well, uh...

1692
01:32:52,413 --> 01:32:54,848
I better be
getting back.

1693
01:32:54,916 --> 01:32:58,351
If you don't feel too tired,
you might wanna sit a spell.

1694
01:32:58,419 --> 01:33:01,054
Okay.

1695
01:33:09,513 --> 01:33:11,898
I'm gonna miss this place.

1696
01:33:13,451 --> 01:33:14,684
Where will you go?

1697
01:33:15,987 --> 01:33:18,454
Not quite sure.

1698
01:33:18,522 --> 01:33:21,557
I have some cat-sitting
prospects in Mexico.

1699
01:33:24,678 --> 01:33:27,280
I thought I'd try
Nueva Rosita.

1700
01:33:27,548 --> 01:33:29,666
It's a little town
I wrote about

1701
01:33:29,734 --> 01:33:32,186
when Jubal was holed up
down in those parts

1702
01:33:32,253 --> 01:33:34,588
hiding out from a posse.

1703
01:33:34,656 --> 01:33:36,756
Figured it'd be
a good place to write.

1704
01:33:36,824 --> 01:33:40,627
I'm glad you're
writing again.

1705
01:33:41,829 --> 01:33:45,732
Flora just loves
the Tony stories.

1706
01:33:45,800 --> 01:33:49,686
So you said.
What about you?

1707
01:33:53,340 --> 01:33:55,776
[sighing]

1708
01:33:55,843 --> 01:33:59,078
I'm greatly fond of them
as well.

1709
01:34:06,671 --> 01:34:08,906
This has been
a wonderful summer.

1710
01:34:11,609 --> 01:34:16,813
There's only one thing
that I know I'll wish
I had done.

1711
01:34:18,216 --> 01:34:19,649
What's that?

1712
01:34:21,719 --> 01:34:24,620
Had our waltz
in the moonlight.

1713
01:34:32,647 --> 01:34:34,481
I know what you mean.

1714
01:34:42,039 --> 01:34:43,606
Sure you don't want
me to take the girls?

1715
01:34:43,674 --> 01:34:45,158
I mean, where
are you gonna sleep?

1716
01:34:45,226 --> 01:34:48,979
Ah, sleeping under the stars
has never been a hardship.

1717
01:34:51,099 --> 01:34:52,132
Well...

1718
01:34:54,736 --> 01:34:57,237
I guess I'll just come back
and get them in the morning.

1719
01:34:59,023 --> 01:35:01,124
Good night, Mrs. O'Neil.

1720
01:35:11,518 --> 01:35:13,053
Good night,
Mr. Wildhorn.

1721
01:35:31,255 --> 01:35:33,190
[snoring]

1722
01:35:36,327 --> 01:35:38,461
He's sleeping.

1723
01:35:44,802 --> 01:35:46,285
[door banging]

1724
01:35:46,354 --> 01:35:47,854
[Spot barking]

1725
01:35:47,921 --> 01:35:51,207
Sorry, Monte.
We were sneaking out.

1726
01:35:51,276 --> 01:35:52,842
We want to surprise Mama.

1727
01:35:52,910 --> 01:35:56,880
Well, your sneaking skills
could use a little work.

1728
01:36:05,156 --> 01:36:07,173
FLORA, WHISPERING: Should we
wake her up?

1729
01:36:07,241 --> 01:36:09,275
WILLOW: No, I think we
should let her sleep.

1730
01:36:09,343 --> 01:36:12,646
When do you think
she'll wake up?

1731
01:36:12,713 --> 01:36:14,931
FINN: Oh, good, you're up.

1732
01:36:17,652 --> 01:36:19,536
Oh, good morning,
girls.

1733
01:36:21,839 --> 01:36:24,641
To what do I owe
this lovely intrusion?

1734
01:36:24,709 --> 01:36:28,111
Here. This is for you.

1735
01:36:28,179 --> 01:36:31,348
Oh, wow!

1736
01:36:35,202 --> 01:36:37,337
[gasping]

1737
01:36:37,405 --> 01:36:40,390
My goodness.
Where...?

1738
01:36:41,241 --> 01:36:42,258
I found it on the island.

1739
01:36:42,526 --> 01:36:46,212
Oh...

1740
01:36:46,280 --> 01:36:48,147
Eat the sandwich.

1741
01:36:48,215 --> 01:36:51,017
I haven't
seen this since--

1742
01:36:51,085 --> 01:36:52,436
Eat the sandwich.

1743
01:36:52,503 --> 01:36:54,287
Okay.

1744
01:36:57,158 --> 01:36:58,724
Mmm...

1745
01:36:58,792 --> 01:37:00,293
Do you like it?

1746
01:37:00,360 --> 01:37:01,495
I love it.

1747
01:37:01,562 --> 01:37:03,796
Come here.
Come here, you three.

1748
01:37:11,822 --> 01:37:14,290
Was the alcohol
defective?

1749
01:37:14,358 --> 01:37:16,626
Changing my ways,
Mahmoud.

1750
01:37:16,694 --> 01:37:18,995
Uh, two Slim Jims, please.

1751
01:37:28,089 --> 01:37:30,924
You know, I'm leaving
tomorrow, Carl.

1752
01:37:30,992 --> 01:37:31,992
Okay.

1753
01:37:35,863 --> 01:37:37,780
Does that mean
I can't be Diego anymore?

1754
01:37:37,848 --> 01:37:41,217
No, you can be anybody
you want to be.

1755
01:37:41,285 --> 01:37:44,421
But I gotta tell you, I kind
of miss that Carl fella.

1756
01:37:44,488 --> 01:37:45,788
He's very special.

1757
01:37:47,625 --> 01:37:49,759
I'm Carl.

1758
01:37:50,694 --> 01:37:52,896
Danged if you're not.

1759
01:37:52,963 --> 01:37:55,799
I wanted to
give you something
to remember me by.

1760
01:38:02,056 --> 01:38:03,623
Fits good.

1761
01:38:03,691 --> 01:38:05,792
A little sweaty.

1762
01:38:07,394 --> 01:38:08,695
So long, partner.

1763
01:38:24,161 --> 01:38:25,462
What are you planting?

1764
01:38:25,530 --> 01:38:27,514
Pumpkins.

1765
01:38:27,581 --> 01:38:30,550
Thought it'd be nice if we grow
our own for Halloween.

1766
01:38:30,618 --> 01:38:32,151
Need some help?

1767
01:38:32,219 --> 01:38:33,303
Sure.

1768
01:38:39,444 --> 01:38:41,711
What do you do?

1769
01:38:41,779 --> 01:38:42,979
Well, it's easy.

1770
01:38:43,047 --> 01:38:47,016
You just dig a little hole
and drop one in.

1771
01:38:47,085 --> 01:38:49,219
I think I can
handle that.

1772
01:38:53,591 --> 01:38:55,658
How is Dad?

1773
01:38:55,726 --> 01:38:57,710
He's okay.

1774
01:38:59,546 --> 01:39:00,680
How are you doing?

1775
01:39:02,550 --> 01:39:03,616
I'm okay.

1776
01:39:03,884 --> 01:39:06,119
What about you?

1777
01:39:06,187 --> 01:39:08,421
What's going on with you,
Willow Tree?

1778
01:39:10,291 --> 01:39:13,426
I never thought about your
parents getting divorced.

1779
01:39:17,265 --> 01:39:18,782
I read your diary.

1780
01:39:22,469 --> 01:39:23,753
I kind of figured.

1781
01:39:25,640 --> 01:39:30,243
It's weird, Mom,
but the fact that
you felt so bad...

1782
01:39:31,846 --> 01:39:33,179
kind of made me
feel better.

1783
01:39:34,982 --> 01:39:38,301
Is that wrong?

1784
01:39:38,369 --> 01:39:39,302
No.

1785
01:39:42,440 --> 01:39:43,640
I'm glad you read it.

1786
01:39:48,779 --> 01:39:52,898
All right, big guy,
Last Chance Saloon.

1787
01:39:54,535 --> 01:39:56,469
Fetch.

1788
01:40:01,508 --> 01:40:04,177
I respect consistency.

1789
01:40:23,030 --> 01:40:26,232
Well, just the person
I wanted to see.

1790
01:40:26,300 --> 01:40:28,501
Come on in.
I got a couple
of things for you.

1791
01:40:33,240 --> 01:40:34,407
There you go.

1792
01:40:34,475 --> 01:40:36,209
$34.

1793
01:40:36,276 --> 01:40:39,178
I'm afraid I'll have
to owe you the 18 cents.

1794
01:40:39,246 --> 01:40:41,747
But you taught me what
you said you would.

1795
01:40:41,815 --> 01:40:45,551
Yeah, but I wasn't
counting on you
teaching me a whole lot.

1796
01:40:45,619 --> 01:40:47,386
Go on, take it.

1797
01:40:49,807 --> 01:40:50,740
Thanks.

1798
01:40:50,808 --> 01:40:53,443
Wait. I ain't done.

1799
01:41:00,818 --> 01:41:02,902
What's this?

1800
01:41:02,970 --> 01:41:06,122
I don't like it
when my fans get short-changed.

1801
01:41:06,190 --> 01:41:08,958
You said you were
missing the last page
of the saga.

1802
01:41:09,026 --> 01:41:12,411
That's what I meant to write
in the first place.

1803
01:41:13,947 --> 01:41:15,982
Wow...

1804
01:41:16,216 --> 01:41:18,518
Now you have
to promise me something.

1805
01:41:18,585 --> 01:41:20,219
Okay.

1806
01:41:20,287 --> 01:41:24,908
Never stop looking
for what's not there.

1807
01:41:27,311 --> 01:41:29,278
I promise.

1808
01:41:29,346 --> 01:41:32,882
Good.

1809
01:41:32,950 --> 01:41:34,684
I'm leaving
early in the morning,

1810
01:41:34,752 --> 01:41:40,323
so we'd best say
our proper good-byes
here and now.

1811
01:41:42,593 --> 01:41:43,993
Do you have to go?

1812
01:41:46,647 --> 01:41:49,215
If I ever had me
a little girl...

1813
01:41:50,651 --> 01:41:52,652
I guess I'd want her to be you.

1814
01:42:41,352 --> 01:42:43,186
Well, I'll be damned.

1815
01:42:48,909 --> 01:42:54,597
[music]

1816
01:43:08,546 --> 01:43:10,012
Be careful with that.

1817
01:43:13,451 --> 01:43:16,419
You sure you'll
be all right with Spot?

1818
01:43:16,487 --> 01:43:18,955
He'll be well
taken care of, Mr. Wildhorn.

1819
01:43:19,022 --> 01:43:22,191
Ah...
I think it's about time

1820
01:43:22,259 --> 01:43:24,026
we dispensed
with the formalities.

1821
01:43:24,094 --> 01:43:26,095
Call me Monte.

1822
01:43:27,665 --> 01:43:28,764
Monte.

1823
01:43:28,832 --> 01:43:30,516
Charlotte.

1824
01:43:32,336 --> 01:43:34,938
It's nice to be
on a first-name basis.

1825
01:43:38,792 --> 01:43:40,043
Well, I think
that's everything.

1826
01:43:40,110 --> 01:43:41,878
But I'll give it
one last look.

1827
01:43:41,946 --> 01:43:43,580
Okay.

1828
01:43:43,647 --> 01:43:45,114
Wait! Wait!

1829
01:43:45,182 --> 01:43:47,299
Wait a second!

1830
01:43:51,004 --> 01:43:53,573
Here. This is for you.

1831
01:43:53,640 --> 01:43:55,291
Do you like it?

1832
01:43:55,359 --> 01:43:59,062
Oh... it's a surprisingly
accurate rendering,

1833
01:43:59,129 --> 01:44:00,880
and I shall cherish it.

1834
01:44:00,948 --> 01:44:02,181
Thank you.

1835
01:44:02,249 --> 01:44:04,901
Remember,
you owe me 18 cents.

1836
01:44:04,968 --> 01:44:08,187
The debt weighs heavily.

1837
01:44:11,859 --> 01:44:16,579
[music]

1838
01:44:40,520 --> 01:44:42,154
Hi, Mom.

1839
01:44:42,222 --> 01:44:44,056
Hey, how was school?

1840
01:44:44,124 --> 01:44:45,591
[together] Good.

1841
01:44:45,658 --> 01:44:46,709
What did you do?

1842
01:44:46,776 --> 01:44:48,294
Nothing.

1843
01:44:48,362 --> 01:44:50,429
Uh-huh.

1844
01:44:50,497 --> 01:44:52,231
Do we have any more Gushers?

1845
01:44:52,299 --> 01:44:53,266
You'll have to check.

1846
01:44:53,333 --> 01:44:54,684
Okay.

1847
01:44:54,751 --> 01:44:55,985
Melanie is such a freak.

1848
01:44:56,052 --> 01:44:57,720
I'm dropping her
as a friend off Facebook.

1849
01:44:57,788 --> 01:44:59,372
Uh-huh.

1850
01:44:59,439 --> 01:45:01,374
And what's going on
with you and Kyle?

1851
01:45:01,441 --> 01:45:05,211
Nothing. Ava says he likes me,
but he's too shy.

1852
01:45:05,278 --> 01:45:07,413
Well, why don't you just
go up and talk to him?

1853
01:45:07,480 --> 01:45:09,665
Mom, you don't know anything.

1854
01:45:09,733 --> 01:45:12,768
[sighing]
Apparently not.

1855
01:45:12,836 --> 01:45:14,770
[cell ring tone sounding]

1856
01:45:19,643 --> 01:45:23,513
[voice of Monte] Charlotte,
sorry I haven't been in touch,

1857
01:45:23,580 --> 01:45:24,997
but it's taken me a while

1858
01:45:25,065 --> 01:45:29,001
to master this e-mail
texting thing.

1859
01:45:29,069 --> 01:45:30,937
I hope the girls
are all doing well,

1860
01:45:31,004 --> 01:45:34,173
and I hope you're keeping up
with your piano playing.

1861
01:45:34,241 --> 01:45:36,242
I've been pretty busy lately.

1862
01:45:36,309 --> 01:45:37,944
I'm happy to report
that I've found

1863
01:45:38,011 --> 01:45:39,779
the perfect place
to write.

1864
01:45:39,847 --> 01:45:43,116
I liked it so much,
I went ahead and bought it.

1865
01:45:43,183 --> 01:45:45,384
Oh, I should say
Jubal bought it.

1866
01:45:45,452 --> 01:45:47,369
I sold the movie rights.

1867
01:45:47,437 --> 01:45:49,521
I'm pretty sure you'd approve.

1868
01:45:49,589 --> 01:45:51,207
[Spot barking]

1869
01:46:08,292 --> 01:46:10,643
Dog Dave
drove a hard bargain.

1870
01:46:10,711 --> 01:46:13,746
Said he would only sell
if I agreed to take Spot.

1871
01:46:16,016 --> 01:46:17,750
What happened to--?

1872
01:46:17,818 --> 01:46:20,219
Mexico?

1873
01:46:20,286 --> 01:46:22,822
Never quite made it.

1874
01:46:22,889 --> 01:46:24,389
A writer needs inspiration.

1875
01:46:24,457 --> 01:46:27,593
And I thought the odds
of seeing you down there.

1876
01:46:27,661 --> 01:46:29,762
Well...

1877
01:46:31,431 --> 01:46:33,682
Monte! Monte's here!
Monte's here!

1878
01:46:33,751 --> 01:46:36,452
Willow, Flora!
Monte's here!

1879
01:46:38,756 --> 01:46:39,856
Monte!

1880
01:46:44,678 --> 01:46:46,412
You come
to visit us, Monte?

1881
01:46:46,480 --> 01:46:47,947
Well, if it's all
the same to you ladies,

1882
01:46:48,015 --> 01:46:50,749
I thought I'd stay a while.

1883
01:46:50,851 --> 01:46:53,769
Looking forward to having
you as a neighbor, Mr. Wildhorn.

1884
01:46:53,837 --> 01:46:55,654
Just keep the noise down,
Mrs. O'Neil.

1885
01:47:03,647 --> 01:47:07,583
[music]

